<TEXT>
eight years ago a folk music group 
from neighboring greece came to this ethnic greek village in 
southern albania the audience waited hours in burning heat but 
neither smiled nor applauded 
a witness said the people turned out to demonstrate ethnic 
identity but dared not show emotion in the albania of stalinist 
dictator enver hoxha 
hoxha died in 1985 and by oct 26 1990 things had changed 
foreign minister antonis samaris of greece was welcomed like a 
20th century messiah when he visited gorandsi and nearby 
derviciani another ethnic greek settlement thousands of people 
surged past uniformed and secret police simply to touch or smile at 
him 
albanias communist rulers have given hints of reform and are 
gradually losing control of the 32 million citizens they repressed 
for half a century 
startling evidence of the change came in july when thousands of 
albanians sought refuge at foreign embassies in tirana the 
capital and were allowed to emigrate 
outside pressure has grown for improvements in human rights 
particularly from the 2 million ethnic albanians in neighboring 
yugoslavia 
if it wants to rejoin europe as it says albania must lift the 
ban on religion imposed in 1967 allow free speech and honor its 
promise made before the mass emigration of passports for all 
wishing to travel abroad 
an illustration of the communist leaderships dilemma was the 
samaras visit to a minority albania says numbers 80000 and greece 
by including all the greek orthodox faithful puts at more than 
400000 
trucks blocked the road to gorandsi samaras stopped his 
motorcade and insisted on his scheduled visit to 1000 people who 
awaited him in the dusk 
men from the sigurimi the albanian secret police were 
sprinkled liberally through the crowds in both villages 
in derviciani a senior albanian official threatened to expel a 
greek journalist who was handing out greeklanguage books to 
children 
a woman identified by greeks as veronika kallas emboldened by 
the rare presence of foreigners defied secret police to slip a 
visa request to a greek journalist she said her husband was in 
jail for trying to flee albania 
it shows you have not forgotten us an excited teenager 
said as the crowd showed samaras the former greek orthodox church 
of gorandsi now a dilapidated storehouse with a faded cross etched 
in the stone portal donkeys grazed in the yard 
a woman gestured her eagerness to pray jars with burnedout wax 
on window sills of the warehouse attested to continued reverence 
for the church 
officials contend religion always was alien to albanians that 
the moslem roman catholic and greek orthodox faiths were imposed 
by occupying outsiders over the centuries recently however the 
authorities removed religion from a list of antistate propaganda 
after religion was outlawed many churches and mosques became 
storehouses or ruins only a few are preserved as historical 
monuments 
albania was the only european nation not to sign the 1975 
helsinki agreements on european security and cooperation which 
include comprehensive human rights provisions 
it now wants to join the conference on security and cooperation 
in europe which resulted from the helsinki accords 
albania may have little idea of what such membership entails it 
has isolated itself from the west for two generations broke with 
moscow in 1968 and with china in 1976 
i tell government officials that joining helsinki means 
nongovernment organizations have the right to come here and ask 
why is this church or mosque closed and to get an answer said 
a foreign official speaking on condition of anonymity they 
simply dont understand what that means 
samaras criticism of the host countrys human rights record 
delivered at a conference of balkan foreign ministers in tirana 
was omitted from albanian media reports 
officials were clearly unnerved by having to deal with the 105 
foreign journalists allowed in for the conference and gently urged 
the last eight to leave to do so before their visas expired 
government secrecy makes it virtually impossible to verify 
numerous rumors of human rights violations 
reports of border shootings or torture often arise in greece or 
yugoslavia both have an interest in painting albania darkly the 
greeks because of their minority in the country and the yugoslavs 
because of the restive ethnic albanian majority in serbias kosovo 
province 
kosovos albanians are far freer than citizens of albania 
despite being stripped of provincial autonomy by serbia hunger for 
crossborder contacts is increasing and hundreds of people a day 
apply for visas at the yugoslav consulate in tirana 
in may acknowledging international pressure for the first time 
the albanian leadership published figures indicating only 35 
political prisoners were held 
aleks lasuari a tirana university legal expert told reporters 
the death sentence is reserved only for severe crimes and that 
only three or four people are executed each year 
how deputy foreign minister sokrat plaka handled the samaras 
trip is an example of the governments quandary 
first he insisted to a reporter that those in the enthusiastic 
crowd around the visitor were complaining that greece was not 
issuing enough visas minutes later he pointed at the smiling 
faces and said you see people are happy here in albania 
</TEXT>
