<TEXT>
a cruise ship recently embarked on its maiden 
voyage with stateoftheart garbage facilities and a promise by 
passengers to be ecofriendly 
its all an effort to set a new standard for an industry 
dependent on pristine waters 
anyone spotted tossing as much as a cigarette butt into the 
waters of the south pacific from the frontier spirit will be fined 
50 said lars wikander president of salenlindblad cruising the 
ship sailed from guam last week 
even biodegradable matter such as food will not be put 
overboard when were in ecologically delicate regions we dont 
want to disturb the feeding and breeding patterns of animal species 
in these areas wikander said from his headquarters in new york 
the 50 million 164passenger frontier spirit will freeze its 
food and plastic waste grind its glass to sand and burn the rest 
through specially filtered incinerators said wikander who 
contends the ship establishes a new nonpolluting standard for the 
cruise industry 
salenlindblad can afford to install this technology its 
passengers tend to be welloff treehugging environmentalists 
willing to pay a little more and follow strict rules in order to 
see exotic locales 
but even mainstream cruise lines pitching more affordable trips 
to middleclass tourists on the welltraveled caribbean circuit are 
trying to make the most of the ecotourism trend 
people who pay for cruises are escaping to the beautiful 
beaches and crystalclear deep blue waters you advertise in your 
brochures dumping trash at sea even though its within the law 
doesnt fit this image coast guard cmdr darryle waldron told an 
international conference of cruise line officials in miami last 
week 
international regulations forbid dumping of plastics anywhere in 
the ocean but glass paper metal and other garbage can legally be 
tossed overboard 25 nautical miles from shore violators face up to 
25000 in fines 
the coast guard has investigated 57 allegations of illegal 
dumping since the regulations took effect in may 1989 and many of 
the charges are brought by cruise ship passengers waldron said 
once 50 passengers signed a letter claiming they saw the crew 
of their cruise ship dump bag after plastic bag over the side 
its very difficult for ship captains to deny that sort of a 
complaint said waldron who wouldnt identify the ship 
cargo vessels and weekend pleasureboaters are responsible for 
most of the ocean debris waldron said but the cruise ships image 
still suffered when volunteers found more than 65 plastic cups and 
shampoo bottles bearing their insignia in a sept 22 beach cleanup 
of florida beaches 
less than 100 items out of the more than 399666 pounds of 
garbage collected in the center for marine conservation cleanup 
doesnt seem like much but the centers gina ruiz says cruise ship 
trash remains troublesome 
what washes up is only a very small sampling of whats 
actually out there its a significant amount of garbage ruiz 
said 
miamibased carnival doesnt plan to fine anybody for throwing 
trash overboard but its passengers are encouraged to separate 
plastics from glass cans and paper into deckside garbage cans 
and on royal caribbeans newer ships huge sewage treatment 
systems and incinerators that burn at 900 degrees fahrenheit take 
all the pollutants out of the waste released into the air and sea 
said spokesman lloyd axelrod 
were always looking at better ways to nurture the 
ecosystem said axelrod by the time were finished with the 
stuff its extremely clean we feel thats very important 
