<TEXT>
ronald reagan has always said hes a sucker 
for heroes one of the heroes who influenced him the most he says 
is franklin d roosevelt 
reagan who often made much of his admiration for the 
conservative calvin coolidge has much more to say of the 
trailblazing roosevelt in his new autobiography an american 
life 
the 40th president often pictured as an opponent of the kind of 
active government that the 32nd president brought to washington 
argues that he was really aiming at lyndon johnson not fdr 
he quotes roosevelt in support of his free trade views says he 
borrowed roosevelts idea of fireside chats to the people and 
agrees with him on the need for compromise in dealing with 
legislators 
he also says he believes roosevelt never intended for some of 
the new deal programs such as relief or welfare to become 
permanent 
reagans linking of himself with fdr gets some support with 
reservations from presidential scholars 
this is not franklin delano reagan although he would very 
much like to be said roosevelt biographer frank freidel 
some of reagans observations are possibly right freidel 
said in a telephone interview adding i have the feeling that 
roosevelt himself was a good bit more conservative than his enemies 
make him out to be 
i think these are all thoughts of hindsight on the part of 
reagan however freidel said certainly the way he was 
campaigning for goldwater in 1964 was not in the spirit of fdr and 
the new deal 
richard neustadt in the new edition of his classic study 
presidential power described reagan as the last roosevelt 
democrat we shall see as president 
reagans links to roosevelt were important for his 
presidency neustadt wrote fdr in 1933 had changed the 
countrys consciousness of what its government should be and do 
reagan aspired to no less if in the opposite direction 
reagan wastes no time bringing up roosevelt in his book on the 
first page of the first chapter he quotes his words that the 
country was dying by inches in the depression by page 66 he is 
saying i soon idolized fdr 
altogether there are 17 entries for roosevelt in the index for 
coolidge whose picture reagan hung in the white house cabinet 
room there are two 
he writes that when he became governor of california some of his 
conservative backers did not want him to compromise with the 
legislature but he agreed with roosevelt who said in 1933 i 
have no expectations of making a hit every time i come to bat what 
i seek is the highest possible batting average 
when the democratic legislature balked at his programs he says 
he decided to appeal over their heads by going on radio and 
television franklin d roosevelt gave me the idea with his 
fireside chats which made an indelible mark on me during the 
depression it worked better than i ever dreamed it would 
later facing opposition in congress as president he writes 
that meant i had to dip into fdrs bag of tricks and take my case 
to the people 
the former president says the late franklin d roosevelt jr 
often told me that his father had said many times his welfare and 
relief programs during the depression were meant only as emergency 
stopgap measures to cope with a crisis not the seeds of what 
others later tried to turn into a permanent welfare state 
in a 1982 diary entry that he quotes reagan wrote the press 
is trying to paint me as now trying to undo the new deal i remind 
them i voted for fdr four times im trying to undo the great 
society it was lbjs war on poverty that led us to our present 
mess 
nevertheless he also says that in the 1930s the democratic 
party began to change drastically as its leaders began 
creating a government that grew ever larger and increasingly 
demanded the right to regulate and plan the social and economic 
life of the country and move into areas best left to private 
enterprise 
one of the links between reagan and roosevelt neustadt said 
was reagans image of office 
freidel said its just that his whole youth was one of 
thinking that roosevelt was quite wonderful and then in later years 
turning toward more conservative matters and still not wanting 
to get rid of this wonderful symbol this man who meant so much to 
him in his youth 
but said roosevelts biographer he is not as much like fdr 
as he thinks he is he is like fdr in that he has charm and 
persuasiveness in conversation and is full of good anecdotes and 
has enormous political skill 
on the other hand roosevelt worried frightfully about the 
people who were out of work who were dispossessed and homeless 
and did what he could for them in areas like this certainly the 
roosevelt image is rather different from the reagan image years of 
prosperity and his rather lack of concern about those at the 
bottom of the pile 
former speaker of the house thomas p oneill jr seems to have 
told reagan much the same thing 
after a telephone conversation with oneill in 1982 the 
president wrote in his diary tip is truly a new deal liberal he 
honestly believes that were promoting welfare for the rich 
 
editors note w dale nelson covered the white house for the 
associated press throughout president reagans second term 
