voters in the states of hidalgo and mexico 
cast ballots sunday for state assemblies and mayors of more than 
200 cities and towns in a key test for the longgoverning 
institutional revolutionary party 
the party of president carlos salinas de gortari now controls 
all but a few municipalities in the two states 
governing party officials told reporters shortly after polls 
closed that they appeared to be ahead in nearly all 121 towns in 
mexico state the countrys largest 
earlier they had told reporters privately that they feared 
losing in at least a handful of towns 
opposition party leaders claimed they would make massive gains 
but turnout was low and that could benefit the governing party 
in many voting stations reporters found no one at all waiting 
to drop ballots into the transparent boxes and despite opposition 
charges of fraud most polling stations appeared orderly 
the most optimistic predictions called for no more than a 35 
percent turnout among 45 million registered voters in the state of 
mexico which borders but does not include mexico city 
opposition parties claimed that supporters of the governing 
party had stolen voting boxes organized caravans of multiple 
voters and interfered with poll watchers charges of fraud are 
common in mexican elections 
the mexico state election commission said it had received 
complaints about incidents involving 84 voting places 23 percent 
of the total but election commissions in both states reported the 
voting was generally peaceful 
eight parties fielded candidates in mexico state and seven in 
neighboring hidalgo but only the institutional revolutionary 
party the conservative national action party and the leftist party 
of the democratic revolution were given much chance to score 
victories 
the results were not to be verified for a week 
the state of mexico is the wealthiest of the countrys 31 
states about 80 percent of the 10 million residents live in urban 
areas around the sprawling federal district of mexico city 
the state includes everything from opulent and middleclass 
suburbs to areas such as chalco and nezahualcoyotl where millions 
of rural newcomers live in unspeakable squalor without water or 
electricity 
the governing party known as the pri from its spanish initials 
hoped to benefit in the election from recent construction of roads 
water systems and other services 
hidalgo is a mountainous rural state with many small villages 
the 914041 registered voters there were electing officials in 84 
municipalities 
while the governing party retains its 61yearold control of 
nearly all aspects of mexican politics its monopoly on power has 
eroded gradually in some regions 
voters in mexico city whose mayor is appointed rather than 
elected voted heavily against salinas in the 1988 presidential 
elections which he won by the most narrow margin in the pris 
history 
national action was expected to show strength in the large urban 
areas around the capital while democratic revolution might win in 
some of the small farming areas near michoacan state home of its 
founder cuauhtemoc cardenas 
cardenas asked for a postponement of the election saying the 
pri had rigged the voter rolls and was preparing a cybernetic 
fraud with computers 
electoral officials dismissed the charges saying cardenas had 
time to make them earlier through the state electoral board 
the pri has been known to resort to fraud and strongarm tactics 
to win elections under salinas however the party has instituted 
internal reforms and promised to abide by the voters will 
the reforms included state primary elections to choose local 
candidates doing away with the appointment of candidates by party 
leaders 
