ban on former coupmakers 
serrano finished third in 1985 presidential elections he also 
took part in a commission that held talks with leftist guerrillas 
aimed at ending the countrys 30year civil war 
there was gloom in the camp of newspaper publisher jorge carpio 
nicolle who had been favored during early polls along with 
serrano and former guatemala city mayor alvaro arzu irigoyen 
no voting disruptions were reported but the violence that has 
marred the long campaign continued to the last minute carpios 
union of the national center said one of its officials in the town 
of el quiche was killed saturday 
on election day however there were no reports of violence or 
interference with the vote said ramiro de leon carpio the federal 
human rights ombudsman 
my impression is that this is a very open honest clean 
election im impressed said us ambassador thomas f stroop 
i hope the vote total is sufficiently big so it cannot be 
attacked as being nonrepresentative 
arturo herbruger asturias president of the supreme electoral 
tribunal said the turnout was not expected to be higher than 60 
percent of 33 million registered voters compared to 69 percent in 
1985 
enough returns to indicate a trend in the results were expected 
by early monday 
the armed forces who cannot vote kept a low profile sunday 
but their armed civil patrols were in evidence in the highlands in 
most places electionday security was left to the police 
guatemala city authorities ordered a special subsidy so that 
people could ride buses free of charge stores and other businesses 
remained closed and the sale of alcoholic beverages was banned 
throughout the day 
a few streets and avenues were strewn with sharp threepronged 
nails to puncture vehicle tires and snarl traffic but residents 
and municipal workers quickly swept the roads clean it wasnt 
known who left the nails leftist guerrillas had called for people 
to boycott the vote 
the winner inherits a 30yearold civil war a bankrupt 
government 60 percent inflation and an epidemic of street crime 
and human rights abuse 
he will also have to contend with a nation where more than 70 
percent of the people live in dire poverty and where the army and 
elite private sector are so powerful that coup rumors are an almost 
daily affair 
the presidential candidates who range from conservative to far 
right filled their campaigns with vague promises to curb crime and 
inflation human rights which implies curbing the armys power 
received scant attention 
guatemalans were also electing a vice president 116 members of 
a new congress 20 delegates to a new central american parliament 
and 300 mayors 
it was the second presidential election since guatemala returned 
from military to civilian rule in 1985 but the high hopes that 
ushered in democracy have already soured to dismay and cynicism 
the corruption and ineptitude of president vinicio cerezos 
government has discredited his christian democrats guatemalas 
largest and bestorganized party and opened the door to an 
electoral freeforall 
cerezo was barred by law from seeking a second term and rios 
montt initially emerged as the frontrunner with a harsh 
lawandorder message 
but he was ruled ineligible and serrano who had served under 
rios montt picked up some of the generals support and became a 
factor 
arzu 44 is from a wealthy guatemalan family and was backed by 
some of the most conservative elements of the private sector he 
has said he would run this nation of 9 million like a business 
enterprise 
carpio 58 who was routed in a 1985 runoff with cerezo was 
backed by a diverse coalition that ranges from the archright to 
disaffected socialists 
the election season brought an outbreak of assassinations 
disappearances and death threats that put guatemala back on the 
international human rights agenda 
it has been an embarrassment for the united states which helped 
provoke 30 years of brutal dictatorship and civil war with leftist 
rebels by backing a military coup against a liberal civilian 
government in 1954 
the united states has poured nearly 1 billion in aid into 
guatemala since civilian rule was restored in 1985 hoping to 
create a showcase for freemarket democracy 
