<TEXT>
soviet high school students who didnt 
know the number of republics in the soviet union would have flunked 
their geography exams a year ago today no one is sure of the 
answer 
lithuania is out or soon to be chuvashia however is in 
latvia estonia karelia and georgia are saying goodbye as fast as 
they prudently can tatarstan komi mari dniester and gagauz are 
ready to take their places 
sometimes its hard to know where you live anymore said 
pyotr gorbanenko a legislator in moldavia which is simultaneously 
seeking independence from the soviet union and trying to put down 
two internal separatist movements 
it used to be simple in 1988 the soviet union had 15 
republics each with its own legislature scattered among them were 
20 smaller autonomous republics or homelands for various 
ethnic groups 
the country has been fragmenting since president mikhail s 
gorbachev loosened moscows grip on power and allowed aggrieved 
minorities to speak out 
that hampers gorbachevs plans for nationwide economic reform 
and getting an agreement among the republics to replace the 1924 
treaty of union it also has led to violence most recently in 
moldavia 
several regions are trying to secede following the lead of 
lithuania which declared independence in march 
in addition to the baltic republics there are strong 
independence movmements in karelia a district of about 140000 
people north of leningrad that wants to join neighboring finland 
the western ukraine where many people want unification with 
poland and the southern republics of armenia georgia and 
azerbaijan 
regions that dont want to leave the soviet union also are 
pushing for sovereignty several regions are actually trying to 
become soviet republics 
some ethnic minorities such as moslem abkhazians in georgia 
want to break away from larger groups they accuse of 
discrimination 
others such as the tatar chuvash komi mari and chukchi 
peoples in the russian republic seek to raise their legal status 
from district to autonomous republic or from autonomous to 
fullfledged republic their goals include political power 
cultural preservation and control of natural resources 
ethnic and political friction has led repeatedly to violence in 
the past two years in moldavia last week the regional government 
sent troops to clear roadblocks set up by separatists who had 
declared a new republic east of the dniester river at least four 
people were killed 
the unrest stemmed from a combination of historical injustices 
ethnic grievances and unfounded rumors a typical mix that shows 
how explosive selfdetermination can be in a nation whose borders 
have changed often in the 20th century 
moldavia which had been a soviet republic since 1924 more than 
doubled in size at the start of world war ii when stalin annexed 
neighboring bessarabia from romania under a secret protocol of his 
nonaggression treaty with hitler 
for the next 45 years soviet leaders relentlessly pursued a 
policy of russification they made russian the official language 
instead of romanian encouraged cultural assimiliation and sent 
russians to run schools industries and political posts 
anatol f plugaru an ethnic moldavian and former member of the 
republics communist party central committee told the associated 
press he had access in 1987 to a list of the moldavian 
nomenklatura the top government business and law enforcement 
jobs controlled by the party 
although russians made up only 15 percent of the republics 43 
million people he said they filled twothirds of those positions 
that began changing last year thanks to gorbachevs reforms 
competitive elections gave ethnic moldavians a parliamentary 
majority including a substantial bloc of delegates aligned with 
the proindependence peoples front 
the new parliament voted in august 1989 to make romanian the 
official language while the law said moldavian citizens retained 
the right to speak russian it required all people in jobs dealing 
with the public from doctors to hairdressers to pass tests in 
romanian by 1995 
protest strikes were held by russians and ukrainians who are 
concentrated within moldavias prewar borders east of the dniester 
they formed yedinstvo a group pressing for moldavia to remain in 
the soviet union 
plugaru claims the russians were were afraid of losing their 
privileged positions which they shouldnt have had to begin 
with 
ilya trombitsky a legislator who sides with the russian 
minority said the language law was a clear attempt to favor one 
ethnic group over another and caused widespread fear of moldavian 
nationalism 
protests also broke out last year in the gagauz region a 
southern corner of moldavia inhabited by about 150000 descendents 
of christian turks who fled religious persecution in bulgaria in 
the early 19th century 
yuri roshka a leader of the moldavian peoples front said 
russians from the dniester area artificially incited discontent in 
gagauz 
gagauz leaders say their people were legitimately angry over the 
language law and lack of investment in their underdeveloped 
agricultural area 
the conflict boiled over this fall when the gagauz and dniester 
regions declared themselves soviet republics and went ahead with 
elections for new legislatures 
plugaru says he is confident moldavia will remain whole and 
gradually move toward independence after convincing gagauz and 
dniester residents they have nothing to fear 
trombitsky said he expects the dniester area to remain part of 
the soviet union while western moldavia eventually reunites with 
romania possibly taking gagauz along 
we are all victims of history he said we must learn to 
respect each others rights because bloodshed is no answer 
