leaders also have demanded greater freedom of expression and 
assembly 
jospin says the protesters gradually are complying with his 
request to be more specific in their demands on thursday he 
promised to push for a swift reassessment of high school education 
and said the students naturally must be heard and included in 
these discussions 
most protesters come from relatively lowincome families and 
many are children of immigrants they view education as the key to 
advancement and resent a seemingly secondclass treatment of 
schools in the highrise slums that ring many major cities 
the government has proposed increasing the education budget by 9 
percent in 1991 which would outpace an overall budget rise of 43 
percent and mark the first time education has been given more money 
than defense 
students worry that improvements wont come quickly enough to 
help them win university admission or decent jobs 
their protests have posed a dilemma for the governing socialist 
party and particularly for president francois mitterrand who has 
enjoyed strong support among youth since taking office in 1981 
mitterrand has stayed on the sidelines but faces increasing 
pressure to intervene or risk alienating his young supporters 
what have we done in 10 years with the immense hope the 
election of francois mitterrand raised asked jean poperen a 
socialist leader we havent changed this society enough and it 
is in the process of taking revenge 
