<TEXT>
a conservative bornagain christian 
jumped to an early lead in guatemalas presidential election today 
but it appeared that the contest would have to be decided by a 
runoff in january 
jorge serrano elias 45 whose resume ranges from close 
collaboration with one of guatemalas last dictators to a stint on 
a national commission promoting democracy and peace talks with 
leftist rebels led with 2809 percent of the vote with about 21 
percent of the total counted 
if none of the 12 candidates gets more than 50 percent of the 
vote there will be a runoff jan 6 it would be the first time in 
guatemalas history that one elected civilian has taken office from 
another 
results broadcast by the supreme electoral tribunal gave 
newspaper publisher jorge carpio nicolle 2317 percent of the vote 
and former guatemala mayor alvaro arzu irigoyen 2237 percent 
the candidate of the incumbent christian democrats alfonso 
cabrera had 1368 percent the other candidates shared the other 
12 percent 
the winner will inherit a 30yearold civil war a bankrupt 
government 60 percent inflation and an epidemic of street crime 
and human rights abuse 
the trend in sundays balloting represents a sharp repudiation 
of the corrupt and inept christian democractic administration of 
president vinicio cerezo who was barred by the constitution from 
running for reelection 
election officials say the turnout appears to be about 60 
percent of 33 million registered voters 
that would be less than in 1985 but more than some observers had 
predicted 
guatemalans also were electing a vice president 116 members of 
a new congress 20 delegates to a new central american parliament 
and 300 mayors 
carpio who has been campaigning for years positioned himself 
as the centrist and assembled a broad coalition ranging from an 
archright running mate to disaffected socialists 
arzu 44 campaigned as a nononsense pragmatist who would run 
guatemala like a business enterprise 
he headed the national tourism agency at a time when guatemala 
was facing international censure because of its human rights 
record 
as mayor he gained high marks for public works projects he is 
from a wealthy old guatemalan family and had the backing of some of 
the most conservative elements of the private sector 
serrano a 45yearold engineer came in third in the 1985 
presidential election and polls had suggested he would fare no 
better this time 
but his old boss retired gen efrain rios montt was forced to 
withdraw due to laws banning former coup instigators from running 
for election that threw an important chunk of votes from the 
religious right into serranos lap 
rios montt is an evangelical preacher who presided over some of 
the worst human rights abuses in guatemalas bloody history until 
he was deposed in 1983 
he had stormed to the head of the crowded field this year on a 
tough lawandorder platform that hit a hugely responsive chord in 
nation bowed by crime and government corruption 
a televised debate with cerezo also gave serrano a boost in 
capital political observers say cerezo debated on behalf of his 
party by law presidents here serve one fiveyear term 
serrano headed rios montts advisory council in 1982 and 1983 
and helped draft a set of electoral laws his campaign literature 
says the job showed serranos faith in democracy 
after the rios montt years serrano went on to carve out his 
own more mainstream niche he was an important member of the 
national reconciliation commission created to work toward 
implementing the 1987 central american accords on regional peace 
and democratization 
the campaign was long and marred by violence and rumors of 
coups but election day was calm 
the federal human rights ombudsman who has logged 264 killings 
and 176 disappearances this year said the the country was 
totally normal without violence or significant reports of 
electoral problems 
five years of democracy has done little to improve everday life 
in guatemala and the challenges that will face the winner are 
immense 
seven out of every 10 guatemalans live in dire poverty and half 
cannot read or write 
the new president also will have to contend with an immensely 
powerful military and one of the most conservative private sectors 
in the hemisphere 
on the bright side peace talks have recently begun in the 
30yearold civil war that has left 100000 dead and more than 
40000 missing almost all at the hands of the military or 
rightwing death squads 
the election season brought an outbreak of assassinations 
disappearances and death threats that put guatemala back on the 
international human rights agenda 
it has been an embarrassment for the united states which helped 
provoke 30 years of brutal dictatorship and civil war with leftist 
rebels by backing a military coup against a liberal civilian 
government in 1954 
the united states has poured nearly 1 billion in aid into 
guatemala since civilian rule was restored in 1985 hoping to 
create a showcase for freemarket democracy 
</TEXT>
