<TEXT>
the nations roman catholic bishops today 
called for sharp limitations on any use of military force by the 
united states in the persian gulf 
they said church principles ruled out any tactics that would 
target civilian lives adding that would mean any gulf conflict 
would have to be a limited war 
the bishops urged that the united states stay the course of 
persistent peaceful and determined pressure against iraq for a 
nonviolent solution 
the action came in the opening session of the annual fall 
meeting of the national conference of catholic bishops 
after lengthy discussion they voted 24915 to endorse a letter 
about the gulf crisis written by los angeles archbishop roger 
mahony head of the conferences international affairs committee 
the letter was sent last week to secretary of state james a 
baker iii 
it said resorting to war would violate principles set down in 
the churchs just war theory by jeopardizing many lives 
raising serious moral questions and undermining the international 
solidarity against iraq 
after affirming the letters position the bishops also voted 
126118 to modify their agenda to hold a special closed session 
later on the gulf crisis 
earlier today the president of the conference said the church 
is in a time of testing for the priesthood 
archbishop daniel e pilarczyk of cincinnati told about 300 
bishops that the clergy seems to be in a period of special 
challenge seminary enrollments down to about a fourth of their 
onetime level have yet to begin climbing from the slump he said 
our priests are fewer and more is being demanded of them than 
ever before he said in his address opening the bishops annual 
fall meeting suspicions have been raised about their 
faithfulness to their commitments 
there have been sad lapses publicly known touching even our 
own bishops conference there are consequent morale problems among 
some of our priests perhaps even among some of us 
pilarczyk appeared to be referring to sexual lapses among some 
priests including a resigned georgia bishop but he did not cite 
specifics 
he pointed out that a world synod of bishops which met last 
month at the vatican strongly affirmed that the priesthood should 
go only to those committed to celibacy 
that has been a church rule since the middle ages but with the 
sharpening shortage of priests many catholics have pressed for a 
priestly option on celibacy 
despite studies finding serious morale problems among clergy 
pilarczyk told fellow prelates 
we may be in a time of testing a period of challenge but i 
know that by and large our priests are happy in their ministry 
and are deeply appreciated by the people they serve 
as the bishops began their fourday meeting a demonstration 
celebrating women was held outside pressing for admission of 
women to the priesthood the womens ordination conference said it 
and about 200 other groups were cosponsoring the block party 
including dancing singing poetry reading and public speaking 
the bishops meeting faced a batch of touchy issues but action 
has been postponed on the most volatile item a proposed pastoral 
teaching document on the role of women 
that was to be discussed thursday but no action was planned 
a draft proposal drawn up in about six years of work and 
hearings was sharply criticized as contradictory and inconsistent 
when it was unveiled earlier this year 
it advocates equality for women but would continue their 
exclusion from ordination 
bishops decided to delay action on the issue after the vatican 
suggested prior consultation with bishops of other countries 
