<TEXT>
death squad slayings summary executions 
and torture have persisted in el salvador since the massacre of six 
jesuit priests by soldiers a year ago a un human rights report 
said monday 
the report blames both the usbacked conservative government 
and the farabundo marti national liberation front rebels for the 
continuation of violence 
thus far in 1990 government action against humanitarian 
trade union peasants and other organizations has continued said 
jose antonio pastor a university professor from spain who compiled 
the annual report 
pastor concluded the leftist rebels also executed suspected 
collaborators and used civilians as cover for their guerrilla 
attacks 
summary killings by the rightists decreased since the san jose 
agreement on human rights was signed july 26 pastor said and 
rebel assassinations of suspected government collaborators ceased 
after that date 
pastors sharpest remarks were directed at the government which 
has been criticized for the fatal shootings of six jesuit priests 
their housekeeper and her daughter by soldiers they were killed 
nov 16 1989 a day after a guerrilla offensive began 
in that case he said there seems to be a lack of cooperation 
on the part of the armed forces which has gone so far as the 
destruction of important evidence 
since the assassination of archbishop oscar arnulfo romero 
during mass in 1980 rightist death squads have seen the clergy as 
fair game for attack 
rightwing elements of the military and government view the 
roman catholic churchs advocacy of human rights and social justice 
as a legal adjunct to the rebel effort to overthrow the system 
it must be concluded that the practice of summary executions 
by elements of the state apparatus in particular members of the 
armed forces persisted in the first nine months of 1990 pastor 
said 
pastor counted 40 politically motivated summary executions of 
civilians by security forces from january to august of 1990 
compared with 51 in the same time span in 1989 according to 
figures from the archdiocesan legal protection office 
the office also listed 46 assassinations by death squads in 
january through august 1990 compared with only 17 such slayings in 
the same months of 1989 the salvadoran governments human rights 
commission counted 42 summary killings by security forces in the 
first eight months of 1990 compared with 68 in the same months of 
1989 the government did not keep figures on death squad activity 
the church recorded 12 assassinations by the rebels in the first 
eight months of the year compared with 30 during those months in 
1989 the government counted 49 in the first eight months compared 
to 173 from january to august 1989 
cases of politically motivated disappearances of individuals 
continue to be reported he added and said that rightist death 
squads were probably behind some of them as well as the 
guerrillas 
torture of prisoners continued pastor found with prisoners who 
belong to political organizations or unions receiving the worst 
treatment 
long periods of interrogation while being blindfolded and 
without being able to sit down or relieve themselves extensive 
beatings the occasional use of a hood which impedes breathing and 
causes fainting immersion of the head in tanks of water electric 
shocks and threats to themselves or their families were common 
he said 
pastor concluded both the rightwing government of president 
alfredo cristiani and the leftist rebels want to improve the human 
rights situation in the country but that abuses continue as the 
war rages on 
rebels launched a civil war in 1979 that has killed at least 
72000 people most of them civilians claiming the government 
represents an oligarchy of landowners and businesses 
