<TEXT>
a protein that a researcher calls the heart 
attack maker is elevated in black americans and could explain 
their increased rate of heart attacks says a study released 
monday 
it is helpful in explaining why some individuals have heart 
attacks at early ages said dr thomas pearson of the mary 
imogene bassett research institute in cooperstown ny 
a study of white and black doctors in their 50s revealed that 
levels of the protein were more than twice as high in the blacks 
pearson said at the annual scientific meeting of the american heart 
association 
the protein called lipoprotein a or lpa is related to and 
probably works like ldl the socalled bad cholesterol pearson 
said 
i call it the heart attack maker he said because it packs 
a double punch like ldl it encourages the clogging of arteries 
but unlike ldl it also interferes with an enzyme that helps to 
dissolve the resulting clots 
last year pearsons study of black and white doctors led him to 
the finding that the risk of heart disease in the black doctors was 
24 times that of the risk in the white doctors 
the discovery of a corresponding difference in lpa levels 
may be a new area to help explain that he said 
we think that lpa is a major major risk factor right up 
there with hypertension for coronary heart disease in blacks 
pearson said 
the study was done on 106 white doctors who graduated from the 
johns hopkins university school of medicine in baltimore and 92 
black graduates of meharry medical college in nashville 
pearson and his colleagues looked not only at lpa levels in 
the doctors but also at their levels of socalled good cholesterol 
or hdl which protects against heart disease 
the researchers found in the whites that the higher their lpa 
level the lower their hdl in the blacks the results were the 
opposite the higher the lpa levels the higher the levels of 
protective hdl 
so why did the black have the increased heart disease risk it 
is certainly hard to understand pearson said but he speculated 
that genetic or other differences between blacks and whites could 
affect lpa levels 
pearson said the close link between lpa levels and heart 
disease risk in blacks means that lpa levels could be used to 
identify blacks who are at risk of heart disease even though their 
other measures of heart disease risk might be normal 
before that can be done however researchers must further 
clarify the role of lpa in heart disease and must devise better 
means of measuring lpa levels pearson said 
so far he said this is still very much on the research 
front 
</TEXT>
