boris yeltsin president of the russian republic 
said monday that russia would not pull out of the soviet union and 
that he would try to settle his jurisdictional disputes with 
president mikhail gorbachev 
yeltsins remarks came a day after he met behind closed doors 
for four hours with gorbachev his longtime political rival 
previous agreements between the leaders have broken down and 
economists said their future cooperation is crucial to solving the 
countrys economic crisis 
speaking to the russian parliaments constitutional commission 
yeltsin emphatically denied that russia the largest of the 15 
soviet republics wants to break up the union 
im for a strong union and union treaty the independent 
interfax news agency quoted him as saying 
gorbachev has been pushing the republics to negotiate a new 
union treaty to transform the country into a confederation of 
sovereign republics such a treaty could slow or perhaps even halt 
the rapid fragmentation that began with lithuanias declaration of 
independence last march 
while yeltsin reiterated his desire for a new treaty he 
insisted russia and the central government must first decide who 
controls the republics banking system natural resources money 
supply and foreign currency earnings 
they pressed us yesterday and earlier first to sign a union 
treaty and then resolve remaining issues in the meantime 
transferring everything to the authority of the center he said 
but we couldnt and will not go for that 
yeltsin said he and gorbachev agreed to set up two parallel 
committees to study how to share control over the economy russia 
has been trying to wrest control over banks natural resources and 
other key economic factors so that it can take faster steps toward 
a market system 
the russian parliament has adopted a 500day blueprint for 
switching from central planning to a marketbased economy although 
it formally voted to begin putting the plan into effect nov 1 it 
has been unable to take concrete steps because it lacks clear 
control of prices currency interest rates land and real estate 
gorbachev and the national legislature have approved a slower 
reform plan that skirts some fundamental issues such as whether to 
break up collective farms the president has called for a 
referendum to decide whether to allow private ownership of land 
two of gorbachevs top economic advisers stanislav shatalin and 
nikolai petrakov joined 11 other economists in an open letter last 
week criticizing gorbachevs tentative reform plan they predicted 
it would increase the budget deficit cause rapid inflation and 
lead to further disintegration of the consumer market already 
marked by shortages of everyday items ranging from gasoline to eggs 
and glass bottles 
yet another leading soviet economist oleg bogomolov criticized 
gorbachevs plan this week as a vague statement of goals rather 
than a map for actual changes 
in an interview published in the weekly magazine ogonyok 
bogomolov said the countrys hopes for emerging from its economic 
crisis rest on cooperation between the center and russia or to 
be more specific between two leaders gorbachev and yeltsin 
ivan silaev prime minister of the russian republic told a news 
conference monday that recent meetings between the republics 
leaders and central government officials have resulted in partial 
agreements on some jurisdictional issues including control over 
foreign currency earnings 
a commentator for the official tass news agency andrei orlov 
wrote monday that gorbachev and yeltsin seem to be doomed to 
cooperation irrespective of their likes and dislikes and their 
political rivalry 
orlov said an agreement in august by the two men to coordinate 
their reforms had fallen apart leaving leadership in disarray as 
the economy worsened and the country approached the brink of an 
abyss 
yeltsin found out that radical reforms were impracticable in 
russia without gorbachevs support as was gorbachevs radical 
transformation of soviet society without russia the tass 
commentator wrote 
