albanians tanjug did not report any violence 
markovics personal popularity grew steadily after he became 
federal premier in march 1989 but his reforms and efforts to 
preserve the federation have been undermined by political 
squabbling and increasing ethnic tensions 
official results were not expected until thursday runoff 
elections will be held nov 25 in districts where no one received 
50 percent of the vote 
turnout was estimated at 75 percent of the 137 million eligible 
voters among macedonias 22 million population 
skopje tv reported that petar gosev leader of the former 
communist party recently renamed the party of democratic change 
won a majority in his skopje district 
gosev supports markovics policies and says he would be prepared 
to form a coalition with markovics party in runoff elections 
a coalition of four nationalist rightwing parties charged 
there was widespread electoral fraud sunday and demanded the 
election be declared invalid 
public opinion polls had indicated the parties probably would 
fare poorly in the balloting 
another contender was the mainly ethnic albanian party of 
democratic prosperity people of albanian origin account for more 
than 20 percent of macedonias population 
western observers said the elections were free and fair 
we were very positively very favorably impressed by the 
fairness of the elections and by the confident manner in which they 
were carried out declared david evans a senior adviser to a 
us congressional commission overseeing human rights and security 
in europe 
