<TEXT>
shadowlands a new play by william 
nicholson is tasteful but not terribly exciting theater an 
evening of intellectual soap opera saved by some superb acting 
the expensivelooking british import which opened over the 
weekend at broadways brooks atkinson theater started life as a 
television drama in england and later was expanded by nicholson 
into a fulllength play its broadcast roots show particularly in 
its cuddly almost cute treatment of oxford dons cantankerous yet 
ultimately lovable 
the most appealing of all is cs lewis the shy incredibly 
decent man who wrote the bestselling chronicles of narnia and 
the screwtape letters 
shadowlands tells the story of the tragic love affair 
between lewis and american poet joy davidman a straightforward 
direct woman who was one of his biggest fans and eventually became 
his wife 
they first meet at her request and the acquaintance blossoms 
into friendship and finally after she ends an unhappy marriage 
romance tragedy specifically bone cancer strikes joy just before 
the first act curtain the rest of the play deals with the couples 
attempt to reconcile their love with her pain 
one of the plays main themes is exactly that if god loves 
us why does he allow us to suffer so much lewis asks in the 
opening scene which takes the form of a lecture by the famous 
author 
pain according to lewis is gods megaphone to rouse a deaf 
world without suffering there is no need for god the man says 
were like blocks of stone out of which the sculptor carves 
the forms of men the blows of his chisel which hurt us so much 
are what makes us perfect he adds 
pain pretty much fills act 2 with joy courageously battling the 
disease before finally succumbing her struggle gives lewis a 
chance to practice what he preaches a difficult assignment he 
accomplishes with remarkable if predictable grace 
what validates shadowlands are the performances of nigel 
hawthorne as the goodhearted lewis and jane alexander as joy his 
lateinlife love hawthorne clothed in rumpled corduroy is a 
teddy bear of a man his portrait of lewis neatly juxtaposes the 
mans towering intellectual genius and his innate shyness theres 
a joy in watching this retiring almost lifelong bachelor finally 
admit that he has found love 
alexander has an even harder task but she manages to bring an 
edge to a series of dying and deathbed scenes that could be merely 
soggy and sentimental 
michael allison gives a beautifully drawn performance as warnie 
lewis brother its a secondfiddle role but allison plays it as 
if he were the leader of the band 
the opulent scenery designed by mark thompson is annoyingly 
busy a large translucent screen keeps dropping in front of the 
settings so scenes can be changed but you still can see the actors 
and stagehands working behind it 
director elijah moshinsky cranks the long play up slowly the 
most cartoonish episodes particularly joys dismissal by lewis 
skeptical colleagues flounder but by the time joy dies the play 
has achieved a certain amount of poignancy 
after her death lewis finds solace in his belief in god and the 
knowledge that there is something beyond the here and now this 
world that seems to us so substantial is no more than the 
shadowlands real life has not begun yet he says and when 
hawthorne says it you really do believe him 
</TEXT>
