the daily news intensified its efforts monday to 
get the tabloid to readers while its striking employees 
counterattacked with a publication telling their side of the bitter 
dispute 
the strikers created an 8page paper called real news using the 
outofwork staff the publication looks somewhat like the news and 
has columns stories and analyses about the strike 
striking driver don robertson said 200000 copies were 
distributed sunday and 250000 more would be on the streets by 
tuesday morning 
the unions planned to keep up their public relations blitz 
tuesday with a breakfast with legislative leaders who support their 
strike 
meanwhile the daily news ran ads over the weekend calling for 
people willing to distribute the paper to come to the news building 
on monday 
a spokeswoman for the paper would not discuss the distribution 
system she also would not provide circulation figures which 
publisher james hoge said last week was at 400000 daily compared 
to prestrike levels of 109 million 
street hawkers some of them hired from among the homeless were 
seen around manhattan monday at sites where the paper has had 
trouble distributing during the strike many vendors have refused 
to sell it while others claim they have received no deliveries 
the strike began oct 25 after a dispute in which some drivers 
walked off the job the news brought in replacement workers that 
night and said that 60 union drivers were out of a job 
the shutdown spread to other unions which have said the paper 
engaged in unfair labor practices a charge the news denies there 
are about 2100 striking union employees 
the paper has continued to be published by management members 
of the newspaper guild who crossed the picket lines and replacement 
workers 
meanwhile there were reports of violence and intimidation of 
news dealers and union charges that the paper has hired goons and 
thugs to attack them as of sunday the police reported 151 
incidents related to the strike with 74 arrests and four police 
officers injured 
while the news says it has held onto its advertisers the citys 
other two daily tabloids have picked up significant amounts of 
advertising since the strike began 
