<TEXT>
american choreographer vic upshaw who brought 
modern jazz styles to france in the mid1960s has died in paris of 
a long illness his family announced monday he was 50 
upshaw died of a serious stomach disorder nov 5 according to a 
spokeswoman for a dance society he worked with 
born in birmingham ala in 1940 upshaw played minor roles in 
the 1958 film version of south pacific and in actress judy 
garlands version of a star is born before moving to france in 
1964 
upshaw designed new routines for the blue bell girls at the 
famed lido cabaret his own dance group the vic upshaw six was a 
staple for years on french television variety shows 
he taught steps to some of frances bestknown show business 
personalities including catherine deneuve sylvie vartan pierre 
mondy and jeanclaude brialy 
in recent years upshaw had brought french cabaret styles to the 
other side of the atlantic splitting his time between homes in 
paris los angeles and hawaii 
upshaw was buried last week in les batignolles a suburb of 
paris his family said no other details about his illness or his 
survivors were disclosed 
</TEXT>
