<TEXT>
rebel leader tin maung win said monday 
that his guerrilla organization has asked burmas largest 
prodemocracy party hard hit by arrests to form a provisional 
government in rebelheld territory 
tin maung win is general secretary of the democratic alliance of 
burma composed of 22 ethnic minority and dissident groups and the 
biggest rebel organization fighting the rangoon government 
he spoke on the eve of a meeting between his alliance and 
members of the national league for democracy 
the league won a big victory in general elections in may but the 
ruling military junta refused to relinquish power last month the 
military arrested four of the leagues few remaining central 
committee members and raided league offices throughout the country 
the military also moved against dissidents among buddhist 
clergy raiding monasteries and arresting monks 
the rebel organization controls about onethird of burma mostly 
areas bordering thailand bangladesh and china 
speaking at the major rebel stronghold of manerplaw along the 
thaiburmese border tin maung win said of his proposal this 
government would only be a temporary one until the nld can stand 
on its own two feet and declare a legitimate government in 
rangoon 
a nationwide prodemocracy movement in burma was bloodily 
crushed by the military in september 1988 aung san suu kyi a 
major figure of that movement and a leader of the league has been 
under house arrest in rangoon since july 1989 
amnesty international the world human rights organization with 
headquarters in london said last week it had reports of widespread 
torture of political detainees in burma a team of un human 
rights investigators left burma on sunday but diplomats stationed 
in rangoon said its activities here were severely restricted by the 
military 
the alliance chief fear exists that the ruling state law and 
order restoration council would totally outlaw the league and so 
it was being offered sanctuary in the liberated zone 
the nld cannot function in rangoon any more let alone form a 
government he told reporters 
the state council has no intention of transferring power 
and continues to suppress any moves toward democracy and so we have 
an obligation to the burmese people to take a definite course of 
action 
how many league members had fled to rebelheld areas was not 
known but scattered reports said both party members and monks had 
fled the cities to avoid arrest 
a dozen ethnic minority groups long have fought the central 
government demanding more autonomy since 1988 students and 
others fleeing repression have joined them in the interior 
</TEXT>
