<TEXT>
germany and poland announced they will 
sign a treaty wednesday affirming their border on the oder and 
neisse rivers laying to rest one of the most intractable disputes 
of the postworld war ii epoch 
german chancellor helmut kohl and polish prime minister tadeusz 
mazowiecki met last thursday on the banks of the oder and agreed to 
settle the issue quickly to begin forging friendly ties between 
poland and the newly reunited german state 
foreign ministers hansdietrich genscher of germany and 
krzysztof skubiszewski of poland are to sign the treaty in a 
ceremony still being arranged in warsaw 
this is a historic event closing a certain chapter 
government spokeswoman malgorzata niezabitowska told the state news 
agency pap on monday only a border which is finally confirmed 
can become a border that unites not divides 
she said that as of wednesday in planning polishgerman 
cooperation we will look only to the future 
in the treaty germany abandons claim to 40000 square miles of 
its former territory in east prussia pomerania and silesia that 
was added to western poland after the war making up for a greater 
expanse of land in the east ceded by poland to the soviet union 
further details were being kept private until after the treaty 
is signed wladyslaw klaczynski spokesman for the polish foreign 
ministry said 
the acquired lands make up about onethird of todays poland 
including such major cities as wroclaw szczecin and gdansk which 
was the germanspeaking free city of dantzig between the world 
wars 
by insisting the polish border be moved so deeply into former 
german territory soviet dictator josef stalin compensated for his 
own seizure of polish lands punished germany for world war ii and 
helped bind poland to moscow as the ultimate guarantor of its 
western frontier 
