ask howell heflin how hes going to vote on 
the nomination of a federal judge and the alabama democrats stock 
reply is that hes leaning straight up 
its a reply that captures heflins sense of humor his 
political philosophy and his wellcultivated image as a man of 
sober judicial temperament 
heflin a former chief justice of the alabama supreme court and 
now chairman of the senate ethics committee will need all the 
judicial temperament he can muster this week when he opens 
politically charged public hearings into the links between five 
senators and charles h keating jr owner of the failed lincoln 
savings and loan 
the panel is trying to determine if 13 million in political 
donations the five senators accepted from keating prompted their 
intervention on his behalf with banking regulators 
heflin throughout his career has portrayed himself as someone 
who is very judicious fair honest and someone who has a judicial 
temperament said patrick cotter a university of alabama 
political scientist 
that reputation has been smudged in recent weeks by gop 
complaints that the panel was delaying a decision to drop the 
investigation of two of the five senators including the only 
republican until after the midterm elections 
when the allegations surfaced on the senate floor heflin 
responded with uncharacteristic haste he dashed off a statement 
accusing his critics of partisan motives and blasting the 
organized campaign of leaks that prompted their charges 
i do not believe that the ethics committee should be placed in 
the position of responding to pressure for the benefit of a friend 
or friends or the disadvantage of enemies or for a party 
position he said 
the committees special counsel recommended in september that 
the case against republican john mccain of arizona and democrat 
john glenn of ohio be dismissed and that investigations proceed 
against democrats alan cranston of california donald w riegle jr 
of michigan and dennis deconcini of arizona 
the committees failure to act on those recommendations sparked 
the preelection partisan recriminations that preceded the panels 
decision to hold public hearings this week on all five senators 
heflin said last week he doesnt know how the hearings will be 
affected by cranstons announcement that he has cancer and will 
have to undergo either surgery or radiation treatment if cranston 
is unavailable he said the committee will have to decide whether 
to proceed without him 
heflin who was reelected to a third term last week with 61 
percent of the vote purposely maintains a low profile on ethics 
cases when his gop opponent tried to make a campaign issue of the 
committees failure to act on the special counsels report heflin 
refused to respond 
just because somebody else breaks an oath that doesnt mean 
that ive got to break mine he said referring to news leaks 
about the report confidentiality is the rule and you have to 
play by the rules 
outside the ethics arena the hulking heflin he stands 
6feet4 and weighs well over 250 pounds is rarely reticent 
hes known as one of the senates best storytellers long before 
he met heflin supreme court justice david souter a new hampshire 
native said he had heard of tieless hawkins and shoeless sam two 
fictional characters heflin has used for decades to entertain 
alabama audiences 
first elected in 1978 heflins senate career has been dominated 
by his efforts to protect home state aerospace defense and 
agricultural interests 
a fiscal conservative whos rarely met a tax increase he 
couldnt oppose heflin has been the most consistent democratic 
vote in the senate for president bush and former president reagan 
the one area where heflin has parted most often with gop 
presidents has been civil rights he supported the civil rights 
bill that bush vetoed this year and has opposed any number of 
republican appointees targeted by civil rights groups 
on the judiciary committee his is one of three swing votes he 
swung against robert borks nomination to the supreme court in 
1987 and for edwin meese controversial nomination to be attorney 
general in 1985 
the ethics spotlight of the keating five hearings will be 
nothing new for heflin he has been chairman or vice chairman of 
the committee during his entire senate career 
he led the 1982 prosecution of new jersey democrat harrison 
williams who resigned before the senate could expel him for his 
role in abscam and earlier this year he led the senate in 
denouncing sen david durenberger rminn for financial 
improprieties 
heflin said he used to enjoy the committee because it let me 
exercise my judicial tools and skills in interpreting ethics laws 
and rulings for his colleagues but not anymore 
now youre dealing with your fellow senators and their 
problems and before long they look at you as being a policeman 
he said when all of this stuff is over ill be seeking 
relief 
