<TEXT>
to serve as mayor more than 25 years is 
remarkable in the most placid of cities but in selma ala joe 
smitherman has survived volcanic selmas racial eruptions to win 
election seven times in retrospect he says if i were black i 
would have agitated too now he says enoughs enough hes 
stepping down at the end of his current term 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
shortly before a heart attack laid him up a 
few weeks ago mayor joe smitherman was ruminating on the formula 
that has kept him in office a quarter century could it be the one 
had something to do with the other 
you start a project he was saying and before you finish 
it start another and before you finish that one start another 
and so on 
be the busiest person in town doing things for selma that the 
people can see and touch it never fails it keeps your friends 
happy and your enemies off balance 
those who know joe smitherman friends and enemies agree he is 
a man of action all right they say he seems driven he runs on 
high test and makes decisions more on gut instinct than deep 
thought a hip shooter on this sunday morning though smitherman 
was in a reflective mood 
the mayor observes a sort of sabbath ritual he rises early 
drives downtown parks behind city hall enters through a back 
door plugs in the coffeepot and meditates for an hour or so 
alone on sunday morning the city hall on many occasions in this 
town the epicenter of shattering tumult is as peaceful as a 
shrine 
the upheaval that rocked selma a generation ago changed the 
political landscape of the south and rippled through the entire 
nation it is where black americans systematically 
disenfranchised won the right freely to vote to have a say in 
their own governance from that day to this joe smitherman has been 
mayor of selma experiencing all the predictable aftershocks 
coffee in hand feet on desk smitherman was saying the other 
day that he intends to leave office when his current fouryear 
term his seventh expires in two years 
selmians as they call themselves have heard that tune before 
in fact in 1979 after 15 years in office smitherman worn out 
stepped aside for a year and gave his gavel to the president of the 
city council when the next election came around he was back in 
the race he has never lost an election this time though 
selmians are betting the heart attack may influence the mayors 
resolve and are wondering what is to become of selma when the 
smitherman reign as one historian calls it in a recent volume 
comes to an end 
selma will do just fine smitherman said it will have to 
because its time for me to go ive walked this tightrope long 
enough and im getting tired do you know how wearing this job can 
be 
wearing yes according to a researcher at the us conference 
of mayors it is rare in this country for anyone to last in that 
office for as long as 25 years that would include mayors of 
complacent towns where nothing much happens to cause a happy 
citizenry to want to change anything 
if such places exist this storied town on the bloodred banks 
of the alabama river surely is not one of them 
whatever happens in selma good or bad has for the past 25 
years been viewed against the backdrop of its past a surprising 
number of visitors still drop by daily to gawk at the city that 
became a symbol its very name a curse a rallying cry for passage 
of the voting rights act back in 1965 
the old conjure women on the riverbank used to whisper the 
legend that stars once fell on alabama a powerful omen the land 
was cursed some in selma find reason to believe it 
a historical marker outside city hall records the two pivotal 
events a hundred years apart that marked their city for all time 
one side commemorates the day in 1865 when yankee soldiers 
sacked the town and burned its confederate arsenal 
the other side commemorates the day in 1965 bloody sunday 
when troopers and mounted deputies whipped and teargassed black 
americans protesting the blatant scheme that denied them the 
ballot 
that event and the 10 angry weeks of demonstrations leading up 
to it occurred the year after joe smitherman took office it fell 
upon him then to preside over what could be called selmas second 
reconstruction 
selma then and now is a city of about 27000 almost equally 
divided racially about 52 percent black but the differences 
between then and now are striking 
the selma where smitherman grew up was a cotton town ravaged by 
the boll weevil and the depression he was born in 1929 the 
youngest of six children of a widowed mother who died when he was 
11 he was raised in a shotgun house on a dirt street in east 
selma the wrong side of the tracks where scrawny chickens 
scratched around outhouses 
back then selma was so rigidly segregated that even the fishing 
ponds side by side were designated colored and white to 
smitherman it was an unquestioned way of life like lining up 
saturdays on water avenue for government surplus food those lines 
though were for both races 
in retrospect said smitherman especially after i took 
office i knew good and well we were wrong if i were black i would 
have agitated too and if i couldnt vote id have been an 
activist probably more extreme than some who came here 
and selma today the mayor likes to take visitors on personal 
tours what they see at first glance could serve as a model of 
civic progress and racial harmony in any region of america side by 
side blacks and whites work live shop worship vote serve on 
the city council and the school board patrol together in police 
cars 
