<TEXT>
at an age when most of their peers are knitting 
sweaters or puttering around in the garden thousands of older 
citizens are trying to catch up with their kids and grandkids on 
the keyboards of their computers computer training centers for 
people 55 and older are springing up across the country 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at age 69 joanna goodblood joined 
the revolution the telecommunications revolution 
i want to know as much about computers as my daughter knows 
says mrs goodblood one of the newest recruits in seniornet a 
nonprofit organization that teaches fundamental computer skills to 
people 55 and older 
seniornet based at the university of san francisco runs 35 
computer training centers in 17 states and canada 
the newest center is at johnson county community college in this 
kansas city suburb where goodblood and 35 others are enrolled in 
three computer classes thirty others are on a waiting list 
a lot of time people when they get old are intimidated by 
technology mrs goodblood says as her classmates peck away on 
their keyboards during their second day of class but this is a 
way to get into it without your feeling like a dodo 
since it started in 1986 seniornet has trained more than 4000 
older adults to use computers about 1100 have signed up for a 
seniornet network that allows them to send and receive messages to 
one another using personal computers linked to a telephone system 
the people in our classes arent in there for their resumes 
says mary furlong an education professor at the university of san 
francisco and a founder of seniornet the majority want to keep 
learning they want to keep up with their children and 
grandchildren 
furlong and a colleague began seniornet in 1983 as a research 
project they wanted to find out whether older people would be 
willing to learn about computers and use them 
industry surveys have found that only 9 percent of adults 60 to 
69 years old own computers and only 3 percent of those older than 
70 by contrast about 20 percent of all us households have 
computers 
what we discovered was older adults were very interested and 
very capable largely because they had more time to learn 
says furlong who coauthored a book titled computers for kids 
over 60 
seniors bring patience and expertise to their computer 
learning she says they find that using computers can open new 
doors for them once they overcome their initial fear of the 
technology 
for a 25 fee members receive a twomonth handson training 
course and a quarterly newsletter they also can make a 15 
membership payment for access to the network that connects them 
with each others computers they are charged 570 an hour for 
their online time 
the computer curriculum includes among other things training 
on how to write letters do newsletters and run budgets furlong 
says 
on the network members go on line every wednesday night to 
correspond and debate issues such as the persian gulf situation 
and the stock market 
many of the students who have ranged in age from 55 to 95 have 
used their computer training for such things as cataloging 
collections and tracking investment portfolios 
im in a lot of groups and a computer would be a convenient 
way of helping me with filekeeping and my records says 
65yearold lee fisher another seniornet student 
the john and mary r markle foundation of new york is the chief 
financial supporter of seniornet which is the first nationwide 
effort to help older adults participate in the telecommunications 
revolution 
computer centers are located in schools community centers 
nursing homes and eyecare centers 
the college was chosen as the site because of its willingness to 
provide its computer education resources says cathie peterson a 
college spokeswoman the college has provided the computers 
computer labs and instructor 
some critics contend that working on computers will contribute 
to the isolation of senior citizens but those involved with 
seniornet disagree 
the communication were trying to establish is like that of a 
park in the 1990s furlong said you may not be able to walk 
across town but if you go on line everybody is right there 
