<TEXT>
she was one of the most celebrated opera singers 
of all time joan sutherland retired last month after a career that 
spanned almost 40 years but hers is a voice that wont soon be 
forgotten her colleagues remember her as a true prima donna who 
worked hard at her craft and didnt put on airs 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when joan sutherland made her italian debut in 
1960 in handels alcina the tough venice audience rose and 
shouted la stupenda 
fans have been calling the australian diva that ever since dame 
joan who recently retired after nearly 40 years has had one of 
the most significant careers in the history of opera 
one of her fans is tenor luciano pavarotti who knows stupendous 
singing when he hears it i think to the world of opera she has 
meant the greatest coloratura soprano of all time he says we 
do not know what giuditta pasta for whom bellini wrote norma 
in 1831 and others sounded like but i dont think they can be 
vocally better than joan sutherland 
lotfi mansouri general director of the san francisco opera has 
directed dame joan in more operas than any other director joan 
is one of the absolutely greatest in the field of opera in the last 
30 years he says i had the great fortune of working with her 
the first time i directed in 1963 it was a production of 
sonnambula by bellini 
mansouris production of the merry widow was dame joans 
last american performance that was a year ago in dallas the same 
city where she first sang opera in the united states 
dame joan retired at 63 in october at the sydney opera house 
less than half a mile from the sydney conservatorium of music where 
she began her career in 1951 tickets for the final performance 
mansouris production of meyerbeers the huguenots cost up to 
415 
she was a unique artist mansouri says she had a very 
extreme vocal range most of the time coloraturas are smaller 
lighter voices joan had a lush middle register she always had a 
very good ear her pitch was always accurate 
maria callas revived the bel canto and the mantle was passed 
to joan she had more vocal flexibility than callas 
dame joans colleagues note that she brought unfamiliar operas 
into the repertoire giving operagoers more variety they talk of 
her as a prima donna who didnt put on airs worked hard and was an 
inspiration 
the only thing she would ever argue about mansouri says 
is she would say youre overestimating my ability 
i asked her in the second act of die fledermaus to dance 
part of the czardas she said are you crazy dancing it and 
singing it at the same time you must be joking then shed go 
ahead and do it she was very game 
the last time i directed her was in toronto in hamlet she 
said im a grandmother you dont want me to do ophelia finally 
i convinced her she was absolutely wonderful her mad scene was 
something ill never forget it was the last new role she ever 
learned 
some critics point out that dame joan didnt always articulate 
consonants her voice was silver like a flute while some 
preferred warmer sounds and her acting sometimes seemed detached 
i dont believe that business that she was not a good 
actress mansouri says she was not an intellectual type 
actress she was very honest sincere she would bring a lot from 
herself 
while dame joan sang operas that other sopranos sing such as 
la traviata she also sang the early 19thcentury operas of 
rossini bellini and donizetti that most others couldnt sing 
the primary interest in those bel canto operas is melody and 
voice the verismo school where realism and big orchestras reign 
began at the end of the 19th century 
tenor alfredo kraus who sang often with dame joan says at 
the same time we are artists we are teachers it is easy to give 
audiences what they know if you give them what they dont know 
you are giving them education 
