<TEXT>
philip kwok was a boy when the chinese 
communists broke their promise 40 years ago and seized his familys 
industrial empire in shanghai 
now hes a leading businessman in hong kong and has founded a 
prochina political party kwok assures the people of this british 
colony that what happened to his family wont happen to them when 
beijing takes over in 1997 
times have changed said kwok 52 we cant let history 
weigh us down 
tell that to jimmy mcgregor 
in 1967 the hardheaded scot then a top colonial official 
braved nail bombs and death threats to help quell 
communistinspired riots in which scores of people were killed 
today mcgregor leads a party that demands more democracy in 
hong kong and greater protection from china 
ive seen what the communists can do the 66yearold lawyer 
said they havent changed a bit 
differences between mcgregor and kwok cut to the heart of hong 
kongs big question about the future how should you deal with the 
communists 
with great deference members of kwoks liberal democratic 
foundation believe 
party members say they are willing to accept limits on freedom 
after 1997 so long as they can maintain hong kongs economic might 
a per capita annual gross national product of 9230 gives the 57 
million people on this collection of rocks the second highest 
living standard in asia after japan 
you cant avoid china kwok said it has to have a say 
to men like mcgregor the economy of hong kong rests on its 
liberties restrict the free exchange of ideas tamper with the 
independent judicial system and the economy will tremble they say 
debate will accelerate as 1997 approaches 
first under the microscope will be chinas promise in a 1984 
treaty with britain to maintain the laissezfaire economic and 
social system for 50 years and allow hong kong to govern itself 
some analysts fear china will try to manipulate the 1991 
election in which fledgling political parties will have their 
first chance at seats on the legislative council 
eighteen of the 60 seats will be filled by direct vote the 
other members will be chosen as all the seats were in the past 
either by government appointment or through elections by special 
interest groups such as teachers and businessmen 
chinawatching contemporary magazine recently reported that 
beijing will donate about 50000 to prochina candidates zhou 
nan chinas highestranking representative in hong kong has said 
it will give moral support to friends 
zhou expressed support for kwoks party in september and 
encouraged cooperation among the numerous prochina groups in hong 
kong 
an unusual alliance between business and labor resulted kwok 
and his party cemented ties with the probeijing hong kong 
