<TEXT>
while hong kongs politicians argue about the 
future most people in hong kong take little interest in politics 
the educated and welloff are worried about getting out or 
getting rich laborers and clerks are too busy working seven days a 
week trying to squeak by 
a government voterregistration drive highlighted the apathy 
many people feel about the british colonys fate after it is 
returned to china in 1997 
more than 700000 was spent on the voter registration campaign 
to pay for television ads a poster campaign and even a rock 
concert the government has held registration drives before but 
this was by far the biggest 
response was so low that the government extended the 
registration deadline by one month to nov 1 the number 
registering totaled 225000 bringing to just over 18 million the 
number of people registered less than half the territorys 37 
million eligible voters 
registering to vote pales before hong kongs burning issues 
emigration and whether lottery tickets should be sold in 
supermarkets 
becoming a voter i dont even know whether im qualified 
said lam chofai a 24yearold university graduate 
a voter has to be 21 years old and a resident of the territory 
for seven years 
i cant see the point in becoming a voter said danny yam a 
24yearold television producer it wont make any difference 
everybody here knows china is the boss and its so pointless to go 
the opposite way your boss wants 
britains last great colony passes to china in 1997 like lam 
many in the territory think china already calls the shots in hong 
kong 
many doubt chinas promise to maintain the colonys capitalist 
economic system for 50 years after it resumes control those doubts 
increased after the military crackdown on the prodemocracy 
movement in china last year 
instead of registering to vote many people are voting with 
their feet more than 1150 emigrate every week this year an 
estimated 62000 people will flee hong kong up 476 percent from 
last year 
analysts say britains colonial tradition is partly to blame for 
the indifference to politics 
after nearly 150 years of colonial rule people in hong kong 
know very little about politics because we have been discouraged to 
educate students on that subject said robert au vice chairman 
of the hong kong professional teachers union 
only recently have high school textbooks mentioned chinahong 
kong relations au said teachers say instruction on the issue 
still emphasizes memorizing information not critical thinking 
another problem is that hong kongs political system gives 
little power to elected officials most poer lies with the 
governor now appointed by britain and to be chosen by china after 
1997 
hosts of radio talk shows quite popular in hong kong say few 
of their listeners bring up politics 
we have a lot more other calls debating whether making lottery 
tickets available for sale in supermarkets would encourage gambling 
among the younger generation said lee luenfai who has a 
morning callin program 
lau chiman another host said people tend to care more about 
their own futures than the territorys future 
many people here reckon their future lies somewhere outside 
hong kong and are trying their best to find ways to emigrate lau 
said 
lately lau said his show has been overwhelmed by callers 
asking whether they qualify to emigrate 
in august the government lined up the territorys leading 
singers to encourage people to vote 
rock star anita mui told a packed house i hope youll join me 
in becoming a voter to demonstrate our support for hong kongs 
future 
one fans response thats easy for her to say she can leave 
whenever she likes 
</TEXT>
