<TEXT>
jean kahn president of the representative council of jewish 
institutions in france issued a statement in august saying 
manifestations of antisemitism in france have sometimes been 
overdramatized in other countries 
we feel this is not justified because it does not reflect 
french reality the statement added except for the tragic 
period of 193945the jews of france for the last 200 years have 
been completely integrated into the national community 
crozier says the jewish element is part of the french 
identity as it is part of the american identity we can accept 
anyone provided he accepts our culture thats why the moslems are 
such a problem they have a culture of their own which we do not 
recognize 
some sociologists and others say this sense of insecurity 
explains the rise of the extremeright national front party of 
jeanmarie le pen le pen contends that traditional french values 
are being corrupted by foreign influences 
le pen who wants to deport north african immigrants says 
france risks becoming an arabicspeaking moslem nation if 
immigration is not stemmed 
the national front the most powerful farright group in europe 
consistently holds about 15 percent of the electorate 
france inherited its moslem population mainly north african 
from its disintegrating colonial empire thousands were lured 
across the mediterranean from 1960 to 1975 to man the factories 
during an economic boom 
tinroofed shantytowns that sprung up around major cities to 
house the workers eventually were razed to make way for concrete 
apartment buildings cut off from city life illmanaged and 
deteriorating these highrise complexes remain the principal 
source of housing for immigrant families 
this is a basic problem which will weigh for years on our 
society said president francois mitterrand in response to 
october riots in a lowcost housing complex outside lyon the 
projects provoke rejection despair and make dialogue 
difficult 
at the moment its hard to find a real frenchman said a 
35yearold algerian theyre all rich and removed 
the algerian who refused to give his name owns the cafe balzac 
at the corner of two housing complexes near vitry south of paris 
he has lived in france since he was a baby but refuses to exercise 
his right to become a french citizen 
they exploited my parents they have done nothing for me he 
said we are badly viewed so why accept something they dont 
really want to give you i have my pride 
many algerians feel they are an unwanted reminder of the 
inglorious eightyear war france vainly waged to keep algeria a 
colony 
france tried early on to rid itself of what clearly was becoming 
the immigrant burden arranging to pay off workers and their 
families willing to return to their homeland the program largely 
failed and officials now grope for ways to promote cultural 
integration 
the immigrant question shares the political agenda with the 
new europe an interloper of another sort 
france has been a driving force toward unity challenging the 
european community to go beyond the open frontiers of 1992 toward 
political union 
but the bravado masks worries that are particularly french how 
to remain rigorously independent in an interdependent community of 
nations and retain the national identity that is it often seems 
frances raison detre 
france currently is facing its most profound identity crisis 
since the advent of the fifth republic in 1958 according to 
gregory flynn a european affairs specialist with the carnegie 
endowment for international peace in washington 
the french he wrote in the wall street journal fear for 
identity more than security and worry about losing all traces of 
their status as a world power 
france appears wellplaced to assume a leadership role in a 
united europe but questions arise about its willingness to 
suppress its nationalistic instincts 
everything is happening as though the french no longer able 
to change the world or protect themselves from it persuaded 
themselves that as a nation they can do nothing at all says the 
governmentordered report on the state of the nation 
the french have long sought to protect their national identity 
politically and culturally the report says from now on they 
will have to choose other criteria for success 
many experts are optimistic 
todd a member of the government panel says france has far more 
confidence now than a few decades ago when the folly of grandeur 
a perverse national obsession bolstered a humiliated nation 
france is one of the european countries changing most 
quickly todd says so its normal that some people have 
doubts nostalgia dream of a peaceful and tranquil france 
crozier says you dont redefine what is french its not an 
intellectual operation its something that just happens 
