<TEXT>
when other children across america are sleeping 
late 48 kids from baltimore and surrounding counties are in 
saturday school dissecting coconuts and scrutinizing current 
events 
the goal to teach them how to think 
nineyearold ayanna harrison reasoned that the swimming death 
of a 15yearold boy with asthma could have been avoided had he 
been honest with his mother 
she might have kept him home or sent a note to school to 
excuse him from swimming if she had known there would be a swimming 
test that day ayanna told her classmates as they closely 
examined a newspaper article about the accident 
that mother didnt think much about him and made him go 
said paul weinberg 10 fingering a paragraph saying the youth 
begged his mother to let him stay home but unaware that he 
faced a swimming test she told him to go to school and get good 
grades 
the mother in fact has said she sent a note to school asking 
that the child be excused from swimming that day 
in two nearby classrooms teachers linda mcclelland and sally 
duff used coconuts to guide sixth and seventh graders in the art of 
observing the biggest problem for the youngsters was finding the 
patience to completely examine the outside before smashing the 
coconut to get the juice and meat discussing the best possible way 
to open the coconut took time too 
and teacher thomas payne explored genetic engineering with his 
eighth and ninth graders to help them formulate meaningful 
questions identify pertinent data and determine fallacies and 
biases 
these youngsters are participating in the saturday school 
program twice a month at coppin state college home of the maryland 
center for thinking studies considered the first of its kind in 
the country the program teaches students how to think in a 
variety of ways not what to think 
we do not teach math or engineering or science or social 
studies said director toni worsham we teach children how to 
solve problems how to make decisions how to become less 
impulsive how not to jump to conclusions and how to be creative 
and look for other possibilities and we deal with real issues 
the national education goals developed by president bush and the 
nations governors stress the importance that students 
particularly college graduates demonstrate an advanced ability 
to think critically communicate effectively and solve problems 
after a year of planning and writing curriculum the saturday 
school opened in september 1989 with about 43 students from 
baltimore and surrounding counties some traveled from as far as 75 
miles to participate this year 48 students are participating the 
goal is to gradually expand to 200 youngsters from kindergartenthrough 
12th grade grouped into classes of 10 to 12 students 
diversity is a priority there are wealthy students and poor 
students blacks and whites hispanics and asians kids from both 
urban and rural backgrounds the students are not necessarily 
gifted 
tuition is 200 a year but scholarships are offered to eligible 
students unable to pay the center has a 100000 state grant and a 
federal grant that varies each year but was approved for 100000 
this year 
on a recent saturday the fourth and fifth graders worked in 
teams pairs and squares to solve problems and make 
predictions teacher mary ellen beatyoferrall coached the groups 
through the frustrating moments that came when each persons 
opinion had to be repeated and considered 
the sixth and seventh graders had to overcome their impatience 
to get done with the outside examination of the coconut and to 
smash it to get at the insides they also took a lot of time 
discussing how best to open it up 
i will never think of a coconut the same way again declared 
12yearold tatiana bareis 
worsham said the most critical issue facing educators today is 
students lack of adequate thinking skills to solve problems or 
make decisions 
although research has shown that nearly all students beyond the 
age of 12 should be able to reason at the formal operational level 
less than 40 percent of high school graduates are able to 
demonstrate higherlevel thinking skills 
at the center active cooperative learning is stressed 
students are encouraged to reflect on their own thinking and to 
learn to manage how they think 
i like being able to teach things that dont necessarily fall 
under the category of a particular discipline said payne who 
works for howard county public schools i like most being able to 
create our own curriculum to have that flexibility is really a 
treat 
duff an instructional specialist in health and science for 
baltimore city public schools said she also enjoys writing 
curriculum and was tickled about the success of the coconut 
curriculum she developed 
school ought to be fun and thinking ought to be fun said 
duff its very exciting to me to think what our kids can do when 
they become thoughtful and aware of themselves as thinkers it 
enhances their selfesteem they feel competent theyre willing to 
be critical politely we hope but still to think independently 
ive seen it happen with my students it makes all the difference 
anita stockton curriculum director said parents receive 
progress reports twice a year but the focus is on the progression 
and growth of the students 
nobody can fail explained stockton a science specialist 
for the maryland state department of education all of our 
students make progress some make greater progress than others 
the students arrive at the saturday school as early as 915 am 
to participate in enrichment activities 30 minutes before class 
there is the weird facts room where youngsters search through 
books that describe unusual phenomena the writing lab or the 
computer rooms where 12 machines are available for students 
interested in solving logic problems 
the threehour class sessions end with a debriefing period 
where students analyze the days activities while completing 
specially designed charts 
the teachers part of a parttime staff that work only on 
saturdays spend 30 minutes after class writing in journals during 
a structured think time before joining together for their own 
debriefing and curriculum review 
the drawback to the program 
after a long pause sin kei yeung 13 blurted why do you 
have to come here so early its saturday you like to sleep 
late 
