<DOCNO> AP901112-0177 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the elderly and prescription drugs can be a 
risky combination and signs of aging may really be adverse drug 
reactions according to a study 
if faulty prescribing is added to the catalog of drug abuse 
then the greatest epidemic of drug abuse in america is among our 
older people the study worst pills best pills concludes 
published two years ago by public citizen health research group 
an enterprise organized by consumer advocate ralph nader the book 
offers a guide to common prescription drugs gives advice on how to 
use them safely and recommends which drugs older people should 
avoid 
some doctors and patients assume that what are actually 
adverse drug reactions are simply signs of aging the study says 
as a result many serious adverse reactions are entirely 
overlooked or not recognized until they have caused serious harm 
the drugs responsible for the most serious adverse reactions in 
older adults are tranquilizers sleeping pills and other drugs 
intended to affect the mind high blood pressure drugs and drugs 
given for abnormal heart rhythms and drugs used to treat 
intestinal problems the study said 
more than 9 million adverse drug reactions occur each year in 
older americans with an estimated 243000 people 60 or over 
hospitalized for such reactions in 1985 the study said 
it said 32000 older adults suffer hip fractures each year 
attributable to druginduced falling and 163000 suffer from 
mental impairment either caused or worsened by drugs 
the study lists several reasons why older people are more prone 
to adverse drug reactions including lower weight a smaller amount 
of water and a larger proportion of fat than younger people 
therefore the amount of drug per pound of body weight or per 
pound of body water will often be much higher in an older adult 
than it would be if the same amount of the drug were given to a 
younger person it said 
and it said drugs that concentrate in fatty tissue may stay in 
the body longer simply because there is more fat 
other factors decreased ability of the liver to process drugs 
decreased ability of the kidneys to clear drugs out of the body and 
increased sensitivity to many drugs 
taking overthecounter drugs in addition to prescription drugs 
also boosts the odds of an adverse reaction it said 
the study asserts that up to twothirds of the prescriptions 
filled by older adults each year fall into three categories 
not needed because the problem is not one for which the drug 
is a proper solution 
needlessly dangerous because a less dangerous drug would give 
the same benefit 
the right drug but with a dose that is unnecessarily high 
causing extra risks without extra benefits 
the study contends a host of illnesses often attributed to old 
age actually can be drug induced 
its list includes depression hallucinations or psychoses 
involuntary twitches of the face arms or legs dizziness on 
standing loss of appetite nausea or vomiting abdominal pain 
bleeding or ulcers constipation diarrhea difficulty urinating or 
urinary incontinence 
the studys advice take an inventory of the drugs you or your 
elderly parents have taken over the last month put samples in a 
bag and take them to your doctor for analysis 
the study includes a list with detailed descriptions of 
possible side effects of 104 prescription drugs older adults 
should not use 
it also offers descriptions of 183 drugs it says are safer 
alternatives 
 
the study is available from public citizen at 12 a copy 
address pills public citizen 2000 p st nw washington dc 
20036 
 
</TEXT>
