<TEXT>
the potato disease that caused europes great 
potato famine in the 19th century was killing potatoes in mexico in 
1947 and the man who has become mr potato went to seek a 
solution 
john niederhauser a plant pathologist who lives in tucson 
recently received the 200000 world food prize for helping develop 
a blightresistant potato 
the award recognizes the achievements of individuals who improve 
the worlds food system said founder norman borlaug a 1970 noble 
peace prize winner and niederhausers achievements have affected 
countries from mexico to bangladesh borlaug said 
although he spent the first eight years of his life in 
washington state on his familys farm niederhauser 73 said he 
first became interested in potatoes while a student at cornell 
university he said he used to select the best potatoes for farmers 
while working summers as a potato inspector for the new york state 
seed inspection service 
but it was not until he had gone to mexico that he earned his 
nickname when a former president of the rockefeller foundation 
george harrar introduced mr potato at a meeting niederhauser 
said its kind of hung around since then niederhauser said 
nowadays hes retired but his agenda remains full ive 
retired four times he said 
niederhauser said he began developing a blightresistant potato 
after accepting a position with the mexicorockefeller foundation 
agricultural program in 1947 
he said he thought twice about leaving his teaching position at 
cornell but i was attracted by the opportunity to work in a 
country in the undeveloped world and help them produce more basic 
food it was different but i felt we were doing something he 
said 
lateblight disease occurs when the lateblight fungus 
scientifically termed phythophthora incestans destroys the 
potatos foilage and eventually the potato itself niederhauser 
said 
the fungus originally is from mexico and is the main reason 
us farmers spray potatoes a practice farmers in developing 
countries cant afford he said 
the blightresistant potato was 15 years in the making 
niederhauser said mexico is the only place where blightresistant 
wild potatoes can grow and they were crossed with cultivated 
potatoes to form an edible blightresistant potato that didnt 
require spraying he said 
niederhauser was one of four foundation members who worked with 
the mexican government scientists and farmers they were paid by 
the foundation but worked as members of mexicos ministry of 
agriculture 
my interest in potatoes gradually increased as i saw problems 
we could help on together he said 
in mexico niederhauser and colleagues helped raise annual 
potato production from 134000 metric tons when they arrived to 
more than 1 million metric tons by 1982 
niederhausers impact however is not limited to mexico he has 
worked in bangladesh colombia india pakistan and turkey with 
scientists and farmers 
though he worked in mexico for 35 years and raised four children 
there with his wife he has traveled around the world 
i spent two years in the soviet union between high school and 
college and worked on farms there he said he studied at the 
agricultural academy in the soviet union in 193536 
he travels around the world recently he returned to mexico to 
help with an international potato project other interested 
countries include poland the netherlands and peru 
when hes not visiting other countries he gives seminars and 
assists with the biosphere ii project in oracle northeast of 
tucson 
biosphere ii is a selfsufficient enclosed miniature model of 
earth beginning in december eight people will spend two years 
studying ways to address pollution and mismanagement of natural 
resources the project also will be a prototype for living space 
the biospherians will be producing their own food including 
potatoes 
