<TEXT>
although estate planning involves more than 
writing a will it is one of the first and most important steps 
in planning for the distribution of your estate 
still 70 percent of americans die without leaving a will 
allowing a state statute to make decisions on what is left to whom 
to test your understanding of wills complete the following 
quiz prepared by emmertt g mcbroom academic associate with the 
college for financial planning select one answer for each 
question 
1 a will is a validly executed document that a once executed 
cannot be changed by you during your lifetime without permission of 
the court b conveys a present interest in property to your 
beneficiaries at the time that it is executed c informs the court 
and your heirs how you would like to have your property distributed 
when you die d only b and c 
2 to be legally valid in colorado laws vary from state to 
state your will must a be a combination of printed material and 
your handwriting b be witnessed by at least three relatives c 
be acknowledged and signed by you in front of at least two 
witnesses and a notary d be filed and recorded with the court 
3 your will legally can accomplish all except a specify the 
rules to be applied if you and your spouse die in a common accident 
where the order of death cannot be determined b establish trusts 
for your spouse or children c name the person that you want to 
receive your interests in your joint tenancy with right of 
survivorship property d direct which assets will be used to pay 
taxes and administrative expenses 
4 the person named in your will to administer the affairs of 
your estate is called a a beneficiary b trustee c guardian d 
personal representative 
5 in selecting the person to name as administrator of your 
estate all of the following are important considerations except a 
fairness and impartiality b low or no administrative fees c 
sufficient time and willingness to serve as administrator d good 
business judgment and experience 
6 your will should be reviewed and revised if a there have 
been major tax law changes b you no longer wish to include a 
particular beneficiary c you marry divorce or have a child d 
all of the above 
7 in colorado the law requires that a decedents will must be 
lodged with the probate court or probate division of the district 
court a within 10 days of death b within 30 days of death c 
within 90 days of death d never there is no requirement to lodge 
a will 
8 only the assets specifically described in your will must be 
probated distributed from the deceased to one or more 
beneficiaries through the courts a true b false 
9 to avoid having certain assets probated upon your death you 
could a create and transfer the assets to a trust prior to your 
death b place some other person on the title as a tenant in 
common c have a will provision that transfers the assets to a 
trust d retitle those assets held in joint tenancy with the 
right of survivorship to name you as the sole owner 
10 only assets that must be probated are subject to federal 
estate tax a true b false 
 
answers 1 c 2 c 3 c 4 d 5 b 6 d 7 a 8 b 9 a 
10 b 
 
some final things to consider 
if you dont have a will consider having one written as soon 
as possible and review it regularly at least annually 
keep a copy of your will in an easytolocate place this does 
not necessarily mean a safe deposit box which may be sealed at 
your death and access by beneficiaries denied send a copy to the 
personal representative executor or executrix 
in addition to your will leave a letter of intent that 
outlines specific final arrangements such as medical care or 
funeral instructions it can expedite the distribution of your 
personal effects instead of waiting for the lengthy probate 
process 
 
the college for financial planning is a nonprofit educational 
institution offering financial planning education to professionals 
throughout the financial services industry 
