<TEXT>
roger frankels golf game is deteriorating 
gerald munitz had hoped to take it easy and spend ore time with 
his wife and six children 
the economic downturn has breathed new life into what had been a 
shunned speciality bankruptcy law and frankel and munitz are 
part of the boom 
law schools report that more students are interested in learning 
about bankruptcy though some prefer to call it corporate 
restructuring 
certainly there is a feeling its a much more stable part of 
the profession right now said june thompson of harvard law 
schools career services office 
the newfound interest in bankruptcy law is due in part to a 
credit crunch among corporations and individuals that took part in 
the wheeling and dealing and spendnow paylater economics of the 
reagan era 
the administrative office of the us courts said the number of 
bankruptcy petitions filed annually nationwide has doubled in the 
past five years to more than 725000 corporate bankruptcies 
comprise less than 10 percent of the total 
most involve individuals seeking a way out from under a mountain 
of debt often caused by running up credit card charges 
frankel a bankruptcy lawyer for 20 years said i have never 
seen it like this in the nations capital 
his fiveday work week of the past is gone since last spring 
hes been on the job 10 hours to 12 hours a day six days a week 
my golf game is suffering seriously i have young kids id 
like to see grow up its difficult he said 
munitz said it is the same in the nations heartland his 
chicago practice is taking up more and more of his time just at 
the point in life when youre hoping to take things easier he 
said 
munitz 57 and a father of six children ranging in age from 11 
to 27 said he would like to see more of them and his wife than his 
work permits 
the sums of money also have changed since he started practicing 
as a young lawyer when someone owed a million dollars that was 
all the money in the world he said its peanuts these days 
were accustomed to dealing with a billion dollars in debt the 
numbers are mindboggling 
the competition for bankruptcy experts has law firms scrambling 
to hire them 
there are a lot more bankruptcy lawyers particularly among 
young people who five or eight year ago turned their nose up at 
this kind of thing said nathan feinstein a bankruptcy expert 
here 
feinstein who heads an american bar association committee on 
bankruptcy law said that in the early 1980s only a handful of the 
nations 200 largest law firms had a bankruptcy department 
today nearly all of them have teams of bankruptcy attorneys 
many have acquired bankruptcy boutiques small firms of perhaps 
a dozen or fewer lawyers who practice the specialty 
the demand has become so great that bankruptcy attorneys have 
been flooded with offers to switch firms feinstein said 
you start worrying if you havent been called by a headhunter 
this week he said 
job placement firms say the hunt for bankruptcy expertise is not 
limited to the traditional financial centers new york los angeles 
and chicago 
the nations capital for example is a sellers market for 
attorneys due only in part to the state of the local economy 
there have been a number of major bankruptcies in the 
washington dc area and a downturn in what once was considered 
a recessionproof real estate market 
the collapse of the national bank of washington alone has 
spawned a cottage industry for lawyers 
more than threedozen lawyers showed up in a federal courtroom 
here recently to handle a spate of cases arising from the banks 
demise 
all i know is the bank lost i lost and the lawyers won 
said luther m hodges former chairman of the banks parent 
company 
some businesses go belly up in bankruptcy and sell off their 
assets but in most bankruptcy proceedings the overextended 
borrower engages in what is called restructuring or reorganization 
creditors are paid a fraction of what they are owed as the debtor 
is placed under strict court scrutiny 
ironically bankruptcies do not necessarily jump when a 
recession hits the opposite may be true as lenders decide its a 
bad time to collect when the value of corporate assets is reduced 
