<TEXT>
savings and loan executives gathering in 
the luxury hotels atop nob hill for their 98th annual convention 
represent a smaller humbler and healthier group of businesses than 
in years past 
fifteen months after enactment of president bushs thrift 
bailout program many of the nations troubled sampls are gone 
closed sold to new owners with government assistance or placed 
under the management of federal regulators 
this years convention of the us league of savings 
institutions which began sunday will be attended by executives 
from the healthiest of the healthy about 600 of the remaining 
2900 sampls according james grohl senior vice president of the 
trade association 
on average they hold tangible capital equal to 43 percent of 
their assets nearly half again as much as required under the 
reforms of last years sampl law grohl said 
capital is a key measure of financial health it is the 
investment of an institutions owner which serves as a cushion to 
absorb loss 
the emphasis on the survivors is evident in the leagues 
changing leadership donald shackelford chairman of state savings 
bank in columbus ohio will be installed as the groups new 
chairman the top elective office in the organization 
shackelford replaces kenneth d seaton chairman of dampn savings 
bank hancock mich and is vaulting over the head of robert b 
obrien chairman of carteret savings bank morristown nj who 
will serve as league vice chairman for a second year 
state savings banks tangible capital is 65 percent of its 
assets placing it among the top 11 percent of institutions 
according to sheshunoff information services an austin texas 
consulting firm 
in contrast dampn has been forced to lay off employees and cut 
its dividend carterets holding company ambase corp is laden 
with debt and losing money 
the incoming guy is symbolic hes mr goodthrift said 
kenneth guenther executive vice president of the independent 
bankers association of america a trade group representing smaller 
communitybased banks 
the leadership has to come from those that are strong those 
that are successful and those that will survive league president 
frederick l webber said catering to the lowest common 
denominator cannot be the case 
the league was once one of the nations most powerful lobbying 
groups but its power has shrunk along with the industry it 
represents this year 2978 sampl executives and their spouses 
league staff members journalists and others are expected to attend 
the convention down from 3862 in 1989 and 5500 in 1988 
the surviving thrift officials are left pondering how to regain 
even a portion of their former clout and their good name 
theyre lepers they know it and theyre unhappy about it 
said financial institution analyst bert ely of alexandria va 
president reagan visited the convention in 1982 george bush did 
the same in 1985 as vice president in other years the convention 
attracted at the very least a cabinet secretary or congressional 
committee chairman 
this year not one member of congress is scheduled to appear 
at least three house incumbents with ties to the sampl industry 
were unseated last week rep john hiler rind accused by his 
opponent of having a prosampl voting record rep charles pashayan 
rcalif who interceded with regulators on behalf of lincoln 
savings and loan owner charles keating and rep denny smith 
rore who sat on the board of a local sampl 
convention headliners this year are housing and urban 
development undersecretary alfred dellibovi and two treasury 
department officials office of thrift supervision director 
timothy ryan and comptroller of the currency robert clarke a bank 
regulator 
the leagues record of success in washington has been mixed this 
year it successfully persuaded the office of thrift supervision to 
relax limits on the dividends struggling but solvent thrifts may 
pay stockholders and to increase the size of the loans healthy 
thrifts may make to one borrower 
but its drive to get congress to dilute rules forcing the 
industry to concentrate 70 percent of its assets on housing went 
nowhere 
the league also hasnt persuaded the thrift office to allow its 
members to convert to state savings banks which operate with fewer 
restrictions on their lending 
next year one of the groups goals will be to prevent congress 
from saddling it with more of the sampl bailout cost another is to 
keep federal deposit insurance from being dramatically scaled back 
