<TEXT>
oklahoma led a list of several major oil 
producing states reporting declines in the number of working oil 
and gas rigs this past week a new survey said monday 
the overall total of working rigs in the united states dropped 
by 20 to 1124 from the previous week baker hughes inc reported 
the decrease attributed partly to bad weather followed several 
weeks of increases that had taken the total to its highest level 
since dec 28 1987 the count a year ago was 1045 the 
houstonbased toolmaker said last week the count improved by 37 
to 1144 
part of that decline good part of it was the weather said 
ike kerridge a vice president at baker hughes oklahoma lost 16 
rigs and we identified 11 of those that cannot move because of wet 
ground oklahoma had about four inches of rain last week 
kerridge said some of the losses were offset by a good 
increase in the offshore drilling rigs 
of the total rigs running as of monday 109 were offshore 26 
were in inland waters and 989 were on land the toolmaker reported 
baker hughes has kept track of the rig count a widely watched 
index of drilling activity since 1940 the count represents the 
number of rigs actively exploring for oil not those producing oil 
at the height of the oil boom in december 1981 the count 
reached a peak of 4500 but the rig count plunged to a low of 663 
after oil prices collapsed in the summer of 1986 
