<DOCNO> AP901112-0207 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
several competitors are trying to break intel 
corps lucrative monopoly over a microprocessor that increasingly 
is the chip of choice for ibm personal computers and compatible 
models 
intels 80386 microprocessor has been a runaway success 
bringing in about a billion dollars a year in revenue and some of 
the highest profit margins the semiconductor industry has ever 
seen said michael slater editor of the newsletter microprocessor 
report 
microprocessors are fingernailsized wafers of silicon 
containing circuitry that acts as the brains of personal computers 
one of the wouldbe interlopers advanced micro devices inc 
began giving private demonstrations monday of its 386 clone at the 
huge comdex computer show here amd removed intels chips from 
several personal computers and replaced them with its own version 
there are no compatibility problems with it it works said 
amd spokesman david frink he said about 20 computer makers are 
testing the chip or have already evaluated it 
a public announcement of the amd microprocessor awaits a 
determination of its price and availability date officials of the 
semiconductor company said 
amd says it used a process called reverse engineering to devise 
a chip that mimics the 386 but uses different circuitry in fact 
amd says its chip is better because it uses less power 
several other semiconductor companies also are working on 386 
clones industry analysts say 
but intel one of the worlds largest semiconductor companies 
is not sitting still while competitors try to chip away at its 
blockbuster product it is involved in a thicket of legal conflicts 
with amd with which it once enjoyed a cooperative relationship 
intel has filed two lawsuits one contending amd has no right to 
a crucial component of the 386 chip called microcode and the 
second charging that amd would infringe on intels trademark if it 
uses the 386 name to market its chip 
on friday a federal judge denied intels request for an 
injunction to block amd from using the 386 name but it was unclear 
whether the ruling would give computer makers who use the amd chip 
the right to call them 386 machines 
the microcode suit stems from a 1976 agreement in which intel 
granted amd the right to the patents and microcode for intel 
microprocessors intel now claims amd may only copy the microcode 
for its own use not to sell chips containing it 
microcode is a set of software instructions contained in a 
memory device on each microprocessor it tells the circuits how to 
process data 
amd based in sunnyvale calif will devise microcode of its 
own to mimic intels if it loses the suit frink said 
amd also is involved in another legal battle with intel that 
could result in amd gaining rights to make a carbon copy of the 386 
chip that dispute now in abritration stems from a 1982 
technologysharing agreement between the two companies 
intel claims amd reneged on the agreement amd says it met the 
terms of the pact and should be given access to the 386 chip as 
well as 500 million in damages 
an arbitrator ruled last month that intel did not act in good 
faith in the dispute but he delayed deciding whether amd should 
gain rights to the 386 chip until another phase of the proceeding 
which is scheduled to start this week 
the lawyers are really doing well over intel and amd said 
slater the newsletter editor 
intels 386 chip introduced in 1985 is becoming the favored 
microprocessor for international business machines corp personal 
computers and clones it is faster than the 286 chip it succeeded 
but not as costly as intels topoftheline 486 
four companies including amd make clones of the 286 chip under 
license from intel said intel spokeswoman pam pollace from the 
companys santa clara calif headquarters 
but no such licenses are planned for the 386 chip despite the 
fact that intel has been rationing its production to customers 
pollace said she said intel expects to meet demand by years end 
dataquest a hightech research firm says 73 million personal 
computers with the 386 chip and its lowercost variant the 386sx 
will be shipped this year 
dataquest projects that shipments of 386based machines will 
grow at a doubledigit pace over the next four years while those 
of computers with the 286 will decline about 7 percent 
</TEXT>
