<TEXT>
a public inquiry into the piper alpha oil rig 
disaster accused occidental petroleum ltd of unsafe practices in 
the july 1988 explosion that killed 167 men 
the inquiry published monday also recommended that 
responsibility for oil platform safety be transferred from 
britains department of energy to the health and safety executive 
the report recommends a thorough overhaul of existing safety 
practices regarding oil rigs and a tough new regime for oil and gas 
companies that own and operate the rigs 
energy secretary john wakeham said he passed the inquirys 
report on to scotlands senior law officer to determine whether 
occidental the piper alpha operator should be prosecuted 
the piper alpha disaster was the worlds worst oil rig 
explosion the platform burst into flames when gas from ruptured 
pipelines caught fire and the emergency systems on the rig failed 
to operate 
the smoke and flames were so intense that rescuing the men on 
the rig by helicopter or lifeboat was impossible the 62 survivors 
reached the sea by rope and hoses and by jumping off the platform 
at no stage was there a systematic attempt to lead men to 
escape the report said 
the report was written by scottish high court judge lord cullen 
who conducted the yearlong inquiry into the disaster 
the government is now acting to implement the recommendation 
for a new regulatory system and to ensure that the lessons of this 
terrible event are fully learnt and fully put into effect 
wakeham said 
cullen said the inquiry found a number of areas in which the 
laiddown procedure was not adhered to and unsafe practices were 
followed he also said occidental was too easily satisfied 
the platform systems were operating correctly the night of the 
disaster 
he criticized occidental for failing to provide proper emergency 
training for its staff and not paying sufficient attention to the 
threat of a major hazard 
he said the energy department conducted inspections on piper 
alpha that were superficial to the point of being of little use 
as a test of safety 
glenn shurtz president of the occidental petroleum corp unit 
rejected cullens criticisms but pledged to do anything to make 
the north sea a safer place to work 
lord cullens report and the profound changes it will bring to 
the whole oil industry will ensure that these men did not lose 
their lives in vain shurtz said 
occidental said it already has implemented many of cullens 
recommendations after studying the evidence at the inquiry 
the uk offshore operators association which represents 36 gas 
and oil companies working in the north sea welcomed the report as 
a blueprint for the future 
director harold hughes said the companies already have spent 
15 billion on improving safety 
he also said giving the health and safety executive 
responsibility for offshore safety would provide a strong 
independent framework to reassure people of oil rig safety 
under the recommendations the health and safety executive would 
have the power to close down rigs if they do not meet new safety 
standards 
