<TEXT>
a leading teachers union official has quit as an 
advisor to the whittle communications service that provides 
commerciallysponsored news programs for classroom viewing 
albert shanker head of the american federation of teachers 
said he was resigning from the channel one council of advisors 
because his membership on the panel left the impression he was 
endorsing advertising in public schools 
but even as he stepped down from the 12member advisory board 
shanker apparently agreed to serve as host of a program for 
teachers that will be carried on a commercialfree companion 
service to channel one 
william gubbins a group editor at whittle communications said 
shanker is scheduled next week to tape the first segment of a 
monthly series the world of teaching an anthology designed 
for teachers 
the program will be carried on a private network that whittle is 
calling the educators channel that service will be delivered over 
the same system that carries channel one a daily 12minute news 
show with advertising for teens in the classroom into an estimated 
5000 schools 
shanker could not be reached monday to comment on his plans the 
aft offices in washington dc were closed for the veterans day 
holiday 
but according to an oct 12 letter sent to whittle chairman 
christopher whittle shanker said he made it clear when he agreed 
to be on the channel one advisory panel that my decision in no 
way constituted an endorsement either of the programming or of 
advertising in the public schools 
in fact i explicitly stated my role would be that of a watch 
dog shanker wrote 
shanker told whittle he should have known that being on the 
council would inevitably lead to the perception that i endorsed 
channel one 
but he said that realization was not driven home until he saw 
his name and picture being used in channel one promotional 
materials 
as a result he said he was resigning the post on the advisory 
council immediately and asked that his name and picture no longer 
be used on channel one promotional materials 
the situation was particularly sensitive for shanker since the 
policymaking arm of the teachers group he heads has gone on record 
against showing tv commercials in the classroom 
he noted the teachers panel also condemned the lack of 
resources that put schools and districts in the position of 
accepting commercials in return for equipment 
schools that agree to show the channel one news show with ads to 
their students every day are loaned a satellite dish videocassette 
recorder and tv monitors for every classroom for as long as they 
show the program 
the same satellite system is used to transmit the channel one 
news show and the educators channel to the schools 
tom ingram a spokesman for whittle communications in knoxville 
tenn said shanker also told the company other commitments had 
made it impossible for him to attend any of the advisory boards 
meetings 
he said whittle has agreed to take shankers name off any new 
promotional materials for channel one although the company will 
continue to use materials already in stock that may include his 
name or picture 
while we are sorry he was not able to participate on the 
advisory board we are excited about still having him on the 
educators network ingram said 
