<TEXT>
fallen junk bond king michael r milken may 
have made an additional 1 billion during the 1980s from limited 
partnerships formed with other drexel burnham lambert inc 
employees congressional investigators claim 
confirming earlier published reports a house staffer said 
monday that information derived from the general accounting office 
an investigative arm of congress indicates milken formed some 30 
partnerships with other employees of the nowbankrupt securities 
firm those partnerships paid out as much as 2 billion between 
1981 and 1989 the house staffer said 
there was no indication how much of that amount was actually 
profit however and the amounts attributed to milken and other 
individuals were only estimates 
the house source who spoke on condition of anonymity also said 
monday that convicted stock speculator ivan f boesky testified 
behind closed doors to the oversight subcommittee of the house 
energy and commerce committee about his dealings with milken 
the oversight subcommittee has been investigating hundreds of 
milkencreated drexel partnerships for several years but no 
evidence of illegal activity has been presented drexel ended the 
practice shortly after it came to light two years ago however 
a spokesman for milken declined comment on the matter 
but a source close to the milken camp noted the information 
about the huge payouts was disclosed shortly before the former head 
of drexels junk bond department is to be sentenced in a massive 
wall street fraud case 
milken pleaded guilty in april to six securitiesrelated felony 
charges and agreed to pay 600 million in penalties he faces up to 
28 years in prison when he is sentencd by a federal judge in new 
york who is expected to set a sentencing date soon 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the oversight 
subcommittee wants milken to testify after his sentencing 
about trading accounts owned by hundreds of limited partnerships he 
formed with drexel coworkers family members and friends 
the partnerships bought up significant percentages of hot junk 
bond issues before they were made available to the general public 
critics say the activity drove up the price of those issues at 
the expense of drexel customers 
federal prosecutors revealed that drexel paid milken mastermind 
of the firms rise to prominence in the highyield highrisk junk 
bond business a total of 11 billion between 1984 and 1987 
including 550 in the final year that 550 million paycheck put 
him the guiness book of world records 
the information stemming from the subcommittee probe while not 
proof of illegal activity suggests the magnitude of the deals and 
how lucrative they could be said the subcommitte source 
the information consisted of a list of 30 limited partnerships 
and the total amount each distributed to investors during the 
1980s 
but the onepage list does not specify individual investors nor 
does it indicate how much of the payouts were profit over and above 
the initial investment 
the subcommittee source said investigators knew from court 
documents what percentage major players in the drexel scandal held 
in the partnerships using that information combined with the 
totals generated by the gao probe you worked backwards to 
estimate amounts received by individuals said the source 
it gives you a pretty good road map in terms of who was 
involved in what he said 
