convention of the us league of savings institutions that he 
believed financial institutions could still earn a good profit as 
housing lenders 
the ranks of the most successful thrifts are dominated by 
those who stuck to the home mortgage business he said 
but he said sampls should also be free as contemplated under 
last years sampl bailout law to move into commercial banking if 
they desired 
the government so far has seized more than 500 failed sampls 
disposing of 300 of them most of the 300 have been turned over to 
banks also so far the thrift office has approved 22 applications 
from healthy thrifts wanting to become banks another 22 
applications are pending 
however he said he remained deeply troubled by sampls 
becoming state savings banks these institutions are similar to 
sampls but have fewer restrictions on how they may invest their 
deposits last years law for instance requires sampls but not 
state savings banks to devote 70 percent of their assets to home 
mortgage loans 
after delivering a speech to some 1300 sampl executives ryan 
told reporters that he was less concerned with the housing 
requirement which also can be circumvented by conversion to either 
a commercial bank or a savings bank and most concerned with sampls 
using conversion to evade bans on buying junk bonds and investing 
directly in speculative real estate development projects 
were not going to put up with that kind of behavior he 
said 
he noted that the federal deposit insurance corp was working on 
regulations to extend the reforms of last years law to savings 
banks in that case he said he would not oppose sampls converting to 
savings banks 
frederick l webber president of the league said most sampls 
want to convert not to evade reforms but to shed themselves of 
expensive examination fees charged by the thrift office 
as sampls fail or convert to banks fewer institutions remain 
behind to support the regulatory apparatus 
ryan drew cheers when he told sampl executives he would cut the 
assessments they pay he said he has already cut spending from a 
planned 330 million this year to 280 million and reduced his 
staff from 3500 to 3000 
despite the reductions he said he would increase the number of 
examiners in the field he said his goal was to examine large 
institutions and those in poor or average condition every year and 
others every 18 months 
ryan also drew cheers when he said he favored simplifying the 
regulatory apparatus so that only one agency regulates financial 
institutions many sampl executives have concluded that they would 
rather be supervised by banking regulators 
on another matter ryan said he was discussing with the 
resolution trust corp which dismantles failed thrifts a plan to 
delay seizing some virtually insolvent institutions 
the rtc has so far taken over more than 500 failed thrifts 
leaving about 2400 still operating privately of those the agency 
considers roughly 170 all but certain to fail 
but because congress adjourned without providing the rtc with 
additional rescue money ryan said his agency was considering 
placing some of the 170 into a supervisory management program 
provided they had little or no continuing losses and stable 
competent management 
when money became available later these sampls will be rescued 
without being transferred to the rtc he said 
</TEXT>
