<TEXT>
mca inc said monday that its 
music unit will shift its 100 million overseas distribution 
business from time warner inc to germanys bertelsmann music 
group 
the deal hands a big chunk of business to bertelsmann at a time 
when mca officials are discussing a buyout for as much as 8 
billion by japans matsushita electric industrial co 
its another example of how entwined the us entertainment 
business has become with overseas companies as worldwide music 
sales approach 20 billion a year with only a third of that 
domestic four of the nations six major record concerns are now 
foreignowned 
bertelsmann music group part of the giant media company 
bertelsmann ag operates in 30 countries and owns labels including 
rca arista zoo and ariola the parent company has indicated it 
will spend 4 billion on entertainment deals over the next three 
years 
the new threeyear deal calls for bertelsmann to give mca 37 
million a year in promotion marketing and other support officials 
of both companies said an important part of the partnership will be 
developing new talent 
mca and bertelsmann said their agreement covers the distribution 
and licensing of mca geffen and grp records 
the licensing agreement is worldwide except for north america 
the united kingdom germany and japan mca has its own company in 
the uk and recently announced it was forming a new record company 
in japan in a joint venture with japanese interests 
mca said it also intends to establish its own record company in 
germany the worlds third largest recordselling territory behind 
north america and japan with about 9 percent of worldwide record 
sales 
bertelsmann music group will be the distributor for that company 
as well as for mcas existing company in the united kingdom mca 
said 
mcas distribution agreement with time warners warner music 
international expires april 1 geffen records had its own deal with 
warner music international and will be distributed by bertelsmann 
beginning jan 1 
</TEXT>
