<TEXT>
county supervisors monday rejected 
chevron usas bid to carry oil from a rich offshore field by tanker 
instead of pipeline 
chevron says it is cheaper to send oil by tanker to refineries 
in los angeles 150 miles south a pipeline is considered the more 
expensive but environmentally safer alternative 
tom rogers chairman of the supervisors said chevron was only 
being held to tough standards it agreed to follow when a permit 
was granted for the offshore project some five years ago 
there is a pipeline available rogers said the symbolism 
is not local government holding up the oil companies if the oil 
companies and local government work something out what is the 
commitment of oil companies to adhere to those agreements 
the supervisors voted 41 after a daylong hearing 
chevron responded angrily saying santa barbara officials are 
not interested in reaching a rational solution 
the 2yearold dispute has idled a 25 billion oil project that 
includes three offshore oil rigs capable of producing up to 100000 
barrels of crude oil each day 
the three rigs hidalgo harvest and hermosa already are in 
place 10 miles off of santa barbara a processing plant and other 
facilities are nearby at point arguello 
chevron usa is lead partner on the project 
the firm sought a temporary fouryear shipping permit it was 
expected chevron would agree to pursue a pipeline operation if 
granted the permit but rogers said the issue was not raised 
rogers said existing pipelines could handle almost all of the 
crude produced by the offshore field sending the oil down to los 
angeles and up to northern california for processing 
they dont own pipelines they own tankers and that would 
maximize profit rogers said 
</TEXT>
